amp-2">Glossary</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Bibliography</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Abbreviations</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>$RS=function(a,b){a=document.getElementById(a);b=document.getElementById(b);for(a.parentNode.removeChild(a);a.firstChild;)b.parentNode.insertBefore(a.firstChild,b);b.parentNode.removeChild(b)};$RS("S:3","P:3")</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"1f:I[411156,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBackMatterPanel\"]\n20:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"21:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"22:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"23:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"24:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"25:T746,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"The Tibetan translation has a colophon telling us that it was made by two ninth-century Indian preceptors‍—Jinamitra and Dānaśīla‍—in conjunction with Bandé Yeshé Dé (mid-eighth to early ninth century), placing the date for its initial translation from Sanskrit into Tibetan in the early ninth century. This date is confirmed by the text’s appearance in both the Denkarma and Phangthangma royal Tibetan catalogs of translated works. Although both royal Tibetan catalogs indicate that this text was originally classified as a sūtra, Butön listed it in different works as both a sūtra and a tantra, and in all Kangyurs it is placed with the tantras of the Action (kriyā) class. In the Degé Kangyur it is presented among the texts of this category related to the principal figure of the tathāgata family (de bzhin gshegs pa’i rigs kyi gtso bo) as one work in a cycle of four that relate to the Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha. The first of the texts in this cycle, The Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones (Toh 503), first describes the aspirations of six other tathāgatas, and then reproduces almost verbatim the content of the present text centered on Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, a passage that takes up half the length of the text. The historical relationship of these two texts remains to be investigated, but the existence of fourth and seventh century ᴄᴇ Chinese translations, as well as of fifth to sixth century Sanskrit manuscripts, of the present work‍—while the longer text only appeared in China in the eighth century‍—strongly suggests that the present work was the first to exist. It has no obvious tantric characteristics and it is perhaps surprising that it is not at least duplicated in the General Sūtra section, like many other works of its kind."])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"26:T52f,Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha is a widely known figure of the Buddhist pantheon in all countries where the Mahāyāna is practiced, and he is familiarly known as the Medicine Buddha or the Buddha of Healing, the short form of his name in Tibetan being Sangyé Menla (sangs rgyas sman bla). As this text demonstrates, his aspirations and activity are by no means confined to the relief of suffering caused by illness, but his popularity stems no doubt from this universally experienced need. A large number of liturgies in the Tibetan Buddhist tradition were written for the purpose of invoking, visualizing, and praying to him, and in these texts as well as in many paintings and murals he is depicted as a blue-colored buddha, holding in his alms bowl a sprig of myrobalan to represent medicinal plants. He is often visualized or depicted surrounded by the other six tathāgatas with which he is associated, accompanied by the two bodhisattvas mentioned in 1.22, and sometimes by the twelve great yakṣa generals mentioned in 1.53. Practices dedicated to him often involve the recitation of the dhāraṇī included in the third text of the cycle, The Dhāraṇī of the Tathāgata Vaiḍūryaprabha (Toh 505), and of the homage and short mantra that compose the fourth, untitled text that we have numbered Toh 505a.27:T52f,Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha is a widely known figure of the Buddhist pantheon in all countries where the Mahāyāna is practiced, and he is familiarly known as the Medicine Buddha or the Buddha of Healing, the short form of his name in Tibetan being Sangyé Menla (sangs rgyas sman bla). As this text demonstrates, his aspirations and activity are by no means confined to the relief of suffering caused by illness, but his popularity stems no doubt from this universally experienced need. A large number of liturgies in the Tibetan Buddhist tradition were written for the purpose of invoking, visualizing, and praying to him, and in these texts as well as in many paintings and murals he is depicted as a blue-colored buddha, holding in his alms bowl a sprig of myrobalan to represent medicinal plants. He is often visualized or depicted surrounded by the other six tathāgatas with which he is associated, accompanied by the two bodhisattvas mentioned in 1.22, and sometimes by the twelve great yakṣa generals mentioned in 1.53. Practices dedicated to him often involve the recitation of the dhāraṇī included in the third text of the cycle, The Dhāraṇī of the Tathāgata Vaiḍūryaprabha (Toh 505), and of the homage and short mantra that compose the fourth, untitled text that we have numbered Toh 505a.28:T46d,“Respected Ānanda, if anointed kṣatriya kings face a threat of injury, disaster, and conflict that is related to an illness, their own or an enemy army, a lunar asterism, a lunar eclipse, a solar eclipse, unseasonable winds and rains, or drought, then those anointed kṣatriya kings should be benevolent toward all beings. If they release their prisoners and perform the aforementioned offering to the blessed Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja, the roots of virtue of those anointed kṣatriya kings and this detailed account of the previous aspiration prayers of the blessed Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja will ensure that the country will be happy, crops will be good, the winds and rains will come on time, and there will be a successful harvest. All the beings who live in that country will be healthy and happy and will abound in supreme joy. The wicked yakṣas, rākṣasas, bhūtas, and piśācas in that country will not harm beings. No evil omens will appear, and the lifespans, complexions, energy, health, and power of those anointed kṣatriya kings will increase.”29:T511,\u003cp\u003eIn Buddhist literature, this is an epithet applied to buddhas, most often to Śākyamuni. The Sanskrit term generally means “possessing fortune,” but in specifically Buddhist contexts it implies that a buddha is in possession of six auspicious qualities (\u003cem class=\"fore"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e) associated with complete awakening. The Tibetan term‍—where \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebcom\u003c/em\u003e is said to refer to “subduing” the four māras, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eldan\u003c/em\u003e to “possessing” the great qualities of buddhahood, and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e’das\u003c/em\u003e to “going beyond” saṃsāra and nirvāṇa‍—possibly reflects the commentarial tradition where the Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e is interpreted, in addition, as “one who destroys the four māras.” This is achieved either by reading \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagnavat\u003c/em\u003e (“one who broke”), or by tracing the word \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e to the root \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√bhañj\u003c/em\u003e (“to break”).\u003c/p\u003e2a:T595,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp\u003eIn the most general sense the devas‍—the term is cognate with the English \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003edivine\u003c/em\u003e‍—are a class of celestial beings who frequently appear in Buddhist texts, often at the head of the assemblies of nonhuman beings who attend and celebrate the teachings of the Buddha Śākyamuni and other buddhas and bodhisattvas. In Buddhist cosmology the devas occupy the highest of the five or six “destinies” (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003egati\u003c/em\u003e) of saṃsāra among which beings take rebirth. The devas reside in the \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003edevalokas\u003c/em\u003e, “heavens” that traditionally number between twenty-six and twenty-eight and are divided between the desire realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ekāmadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), form realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpadhātu\u003c/em\u003e), and formless realm (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eārūpyadhātu\u003c/em\u003e). A being attains rebirth among the devas either through meritorious deeds (in the desire realm) or the attainment of subtle meditative states (in the form and formless realms). While rebirth among the devas is considered favorable, it is ultimately a transitory state from which beings will fall when the conditions that lead to rebirth there are exhausted. Thus, rebirth in the god realms is regarded as a diversion from the spiritual path. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"2b:T456,\u003cp\u003eA frequently used synonym for \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003ebuddha\u003c/em\u003e. According to different explanations, it can be read as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-gata\u003c/em\u003e, literally meaning “one who has thus gone,” or as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-āgata\u003c/em\u003e, “one who has thus come.” \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eGata\u003c/em\u003e, though literally meaning “gone,” is a past passive participle used to describe a state or condition of existence. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eTatha­(tā)\u003c/em\u003e, often rendered as “suchness” or “thusness,” is the quality or condition of things as they really are, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms. Therefore, this epithet is interpreted in different ways, but in general it implies one who has departed in the wake of the buddhas of the past, or one who has manifested the supreme awakening dependent on the reality that does not abide in the two extremes of existence and quiescence. It is also often used as a specific epithet of the Buddha Śākyamuni.\u003c/p\u003e2c:T97d,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eAn ideal monarch or emperor who, as the result of the merit accumulated in previous lifetimes, rules over a vast realm in accordance with the Dharma. Such a monarch is called a \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecakravartin\u003c/em\u003e because he bears a wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ecakra\u003c/em\u003e) that rolls (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003evartate\u003c/em\u003e) across the earth, bringing all lands and kingdoms under his power. The cakravartin conquers his territory without causing harm, and his activity causes beings to enter the path of wholesome actions. According to Vasubandhu’s \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, just as with the buddhas, only one cakravartin appears in a world system at any given time. They are likewise endowed with the thirty-two major marks of a great being (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003emahāpuruṣalakṣaṇa\u003c/em\u003e), but a cakravartin’s marks are outshined by those of a buddha. They possess seven precious objects: the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the wish-fulfilling gem, the queen, the general, and the minister. An illustrative passage about the cakravartin and his possessions can be found in \u003ccite class=\"title text-en\" lang=\"en\"\u003eThe Play in Full\u003c/cite\u003e (Toh 95), \u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html#UT22084-046-001-94\" title=\"3.3\"\u003e3.3\u003c/a\u003e–\u003ca target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh95.html#UT22084-046-001-104\" title=\"3.13\"\u003e3.13\u003c/a\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eVasubandhu lists four types of cakravartins: (1) the cakravartin with a golden wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003esuvarṇacakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over four continents and is invited by lesser kings to be their ruler; (2) the cakravartin with a silver wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003erūpyacakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over three continents and his opponents submit to him as he approaches; (3) the cakravartin with a copper wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etāmracakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over two continents and his opponents submit themselves after preparing for battle; and (4) the cakravartin with an iron wheel (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eayaścakravartin\u003c/em\u003e) rules over one continent and his opponents submit themselves after brandishing weapons. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"18:[\"$\",\"$L1f\",null,{\"abbreviations\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4126a180-90a4-479e-a023-c353c46ee9e9\",\"sort\":1199,\"type\":\"abbreviationsHeader\",\"label\":\"ab.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":13,\"uuid\":\"42410aec-11c6-464e-a457-3b5ae5a315b4\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Abbreviations\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7aa89e82-ab2d-443a-a007-8d51b3bd9274\",\"sort\":1200,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25,\"uuid\":\"9ed67860-01f9-4d18-88be-1c00b6f985c6\",\"level\":5},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sigla for Tibetan Sources\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1c4ad633-db6c-4663-93c6-930fc8a58554\",\"sort\":1201,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":14,\"uuid\":\"1c4ad633-db6c-4663-93c6-930fc8a58554\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"D \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"1c4ad633-db6c-4663-93c6-930fc8a58554\",\"uuid\":\"53de3b21-0a84-4adf-afeb-58da8a565f37\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"D \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Degé Kangyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":14,\"abbreviation\":\"1c4ad633-db6c-4663-93c6-930fc8a58554\",\"uuid\":\"1307902d-7f8e-4c11-8f61-a08c2156206a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Degé Kangyur\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c02bd449-5e51-4276-91d6-ed523518e968\",\"sort\":1203,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"c02bd449-5e51-4276-91d6-ed523518e968\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"K \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"c02bd449-5e51-4276-91d6-ed523518e968\",\"uuid\":\"dc8591bf-e0da-4311-958d-94b4eb824935\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"K \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Kangxi Kangyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":16,\"abbreviation\":\"c02bd449-5e51-4276-91d6-ed523518e968\",\"uuid\":\"aa50c45b-2191-43ad-9477-36607f3b26ef\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kangxi Kangyur\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23011033-39af-4b9e-9836-caf2b17a80de\",\"sort\":1205,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"23011033-39af-4b9e-9836-caf2b17a80de\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"S \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"23011033-39af-4b9e-9836-caf2b17a80de\",\"uuid\":\"eddba50e-2cb3-4dd3-933e-0fc89c8d0dd1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"S \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Stok Palace MS Kangyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":24,\"abbreviation\":\"23011033-39af-4b9e-9836-caf2b17a80de\",\"uuid\":\"dc11b13b-cc8b-444f-8366-5883fee5e74b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Stok Palace MS Kangyur\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"47c51433-00dd-4f98-a60a-8f7124f51d67\",\"sort\":1207,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"47c51433-00dd-4f98-a60a-8f7124f51d67\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"Y \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"47c51433-00dd-4f98-a60a-8f7124f51d67\",\"uuid\":\"f7e34a0b-a068-4b24-a858-36b76edc1835\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Y \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Yongle Kangyur\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":16,\"abbreviation\":\"47c51433-00dd-4f98-a60a-8f7124f51d67\",\"uuid\":\"da7bb99e-18d1-4e86-b7d1-b4d472f384e9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yongle Kangyur\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d61357df-b7f5-4d3c-9979-f73987b25b5f\",\"sort\":1209,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27,\"uuid\":\"853f6bbe-c5ba-46a7-9493-82d81126bd23\",\"level\":5},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sigla for Sanskrit Editions\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d55610eb-1f8d-4d21-afa3-0f26c329064d\",\"sort\":1210,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"d55610eb-1f8d-4d21-afa3-0f26c329064d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"G \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"d55610eb-1f8d-4d21-afa3-0f26c329064d\",\"uuid\":\"6defa4c6-18d5-4869-a64d-4a8204cf2ab6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"G \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Dutt et al.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":37,\"abbreviation\":\"d55610eb-1f8d-4d21-afa3-0f26c329064d\",\"uuid\":\"3f4264c4-e645-40fe-aedf-3314f3ce0502\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Dutt et al.\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8189b41c-6110-4bfe-ba95-a3cb6bb50ad4\",\"sort\":1213,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"8189b41c-6110-4bfe-ba95-a3cb6bb50ad4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"SC \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3,\"abbreviation\":\"8189b41c-6110-4bfe-ba95-a3cb6bb50ad4\",\"uuid\":\"d2ab3a19-03a8-404e-a4ee-464585158a98\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"SC \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Schopen\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":34,\"abbreviation\":\"8189b41c-6110-4bfe-ba95-a3cb6bb50ad4\",\"uuid\":\"16a26e98-42f7-4a52-ba02-a8f1861f278b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Schopen\"}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f41bdc76-d2a7-4e03-bddb-5d72d2a03cc7\",\"sort\":1217,\"type\":\"abbreviations\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"class\":\"flex flex-row gap-2\",\"start\":0,\"end\":32,\"uuid\":\"f41bdc76-d2a7-4e03-bddb-5d72d2a03cc7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"abbreviation\",\"text\":\"V \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":2,\"abbreviation\":\"f41bdc76-d2a7-4e03-bddb-5d72d2a03cc7\",\"uuid\":\"541638a5-e278-4b42-9b37-4b43d646c802\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V \"}]},{\"type\":\"hasAbbreviation\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Vaidya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":2,\"end\":32,\"abbreviation\":\"f41bdc76-d2a7-4e03-bddb-5d72d2a03cc7\",\"uuid\":\"59b3203e-4ad7-4bad-a25d-205a9ad78449\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra in Vaidya\"}]}]}]}],\"bibliography\":[{\"heading\":\"Tibetan Sources\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"c39078eb-5995-4e1e-a5d3-a78be259d767\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa bcom ldan ’das sman gyi bla bai Dur+ya’i ’od gyi smon lam gyi khyad par rgyas pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eĀrya­bhagavān­bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabhasya­ pūrva­praṇidhāna­viśeṣa­vistāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 504, Degé Kangyur vol. 87 (rgyud ’bum, da), folios 274.a–283.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4ac6bbba-f088-4e9a-8de3-6818a74dde0f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa bcom ldan ’das sman gyi bla bai Dur+ya’i ’od gyi smon lam gyi khyad par rgyas pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eĀrya­bhagavān­bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabhasya­ pūrva­praṇidhāna­viśeṣa­vistāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). bka’ ’gyur (dpe bsdur ma) [Comparative Edition of the Kangyur], krung go’i bod rig pa zhib ’jug ste gnas kyi bka’ bstan dpe sdur khang (The Tibetan Tripitaka Collation Bureau of the China Tibetology Research Center). 108 volumes. Beijing: krung go’i bod rig pa dpe skrun khang (China Tibetology Publishing House) 2006–9, vol. 87, pp. 814–36.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"9af4575c-1ccb-406b-b64f-92ae337ba802\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa bcom ldan ’das sman gyi bla bai Dur+ya’i ’od gyi smon lam gyi khyad par rgyas pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eĀrya­bhagavān­bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabhasya ­pūrva­praṇidhāna­viśeṣa­vistāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e). Stok Palace Kangyur vol. 72 (mdo, zha), folios 268.a–282.a. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"fd79a63c-60c4-4a2f-ae51-eafa86c0af33\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa de bzhin gshegs pa bdun gyi sngon gyi smon lam gyi khyad par rgyas pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eĀrya­sapta­tathāgata­pūrva­praṇidhāna­viśeṣa­vistāra­nāma­mahāyāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e) [\u003cem\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones\u003c/em\u003e]. Toh 503, Degé Kangyur vol. 87 (rgyud ’bum, da), folios 248.b–273.b. English translation in Dharmachakra Translations Committee (2021).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4030dbf2-375d-4b46-9741-d1cd43945f8f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e’phags pa de bzhin gshegs pa’i ting nge ’dzin gyi stobs bskyed pa bai DUr+ya’i ’od ces bya ba’i gzungs\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eĀrya­tathāgata­vaiḍūrya­prabha­nāma­balādhāna­samādhi­dhāraṇī\u003c/em\u003e) [\u003cem\u003eThe Dhāraṇī of the Tathāgata Vaiḍūryaprabha\u003c/em\u003e]. Toh 505, Degé Kangyur vol. 87 (rgyud ’bum, da), folios 284.a–286.a. English translation in \u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh505.html\\\"\u003e84000 Translation Team 2024\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"74ed467e-4134-4b42-b24c-1fa8f5e64cf5\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003epho brang stod thang ldan dkar gyi chos kyi ’gyur ro cog gi dkar chag\u003c/em\u003e [Denkarma]. Toh 4364, Degé Tengyur vol. 206 (sna tshogs, jo), folios 294.b–310.a.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"f64f5152-007f-4801-ada1-5d2e93b8c76e\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eŚāntideva. \u003cem\u003ebslab pa kun las btus pa’i mngon par rtogs pa\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eŚikṣāsamuccaya\u003c/em\u003e). Toh 3940, Degé Tengyur vol. 111 (dbu ma, khi), folios 3.a–194.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"fd851dc5-2135-45a2-868e-82c10ec7f0c5\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003esman gtong ba’i tshe sman la sngags kyis gdab pa\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 505a, Degé Kangyur vol. 87 (rgyud ’bum, da), folio 286.a. English translation in \u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh505a.html\\\"\u003eDalton 2023\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Sanskrit Sources\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"a49a0a3f-6c51-4b3d-bac3-caef4e493a2f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eBendall, Cecil, ed. \u003cem\u003eÇikshāsamuccaya: A Compendium of Buddhistic Teaching Compiled by Çāntideva, Chiefly from Earlier Mahāyāna-Sūtras\u003c/em\u003e. Bibliotheca Buddhica 1. St. Petersburg: Académie Impériale des Sciences, 1902.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"59cca878-8b99-4f6f-91fa-bce8c35c9331\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDutt, Nalinaksha, D. M. Bhattacharya, and Vidyavaridhi Shiv Nath Sharma, eds. “Bhaiṣajya­guru-sūtram.” In \u003cem\u003eGilgit Manuscripts Vol. I\u003c/em\u003e, 1–32. Calcutta: Calcutta Oriental Press, 1939. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"7a328042-8a34-462c-a548-064907b20028\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eSchopen, Gregory. “The \u003cem\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru-Sūtra\u003c/em\u003e and the Buddhism of Gilgit.” PhD diss., Australian National University, 1978. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"45cd117f-7621-4a86-941b-4ee1f8a9f238\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eVaidya, P. L., ed. \u003cem\u003eMahāyāna-sūtra-saṁgraha: Part I\u003c/em\u003e. Buddhist Sanskrit Texts 17. Darbhanga: Mithila Institute, 1961.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Reference Works\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"88292ab1-55b8-4b4f-b165-87cf3f421fa7\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eButön Rinchen Drup (bu ston rin chen grub). \u003cem\u003echos ’byung\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003ebde bar gshegs pa’i bstan pa’i gsal byed chos kyi ’byung gnas gsung rab rin po che’i gter mdzod\u003c/em\u003e). In \u003cem\u003egsung ’bum/ rin chen grub/ zhol par ma/ ldi lir bskyar par brgyab pa/\u003c/em\u003e, vol. 24 (ya), pp. 633–1055. New Delhi: International Academy of Indian Culture, 1965–71.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"4a194bf7-43de-4e1f-9daa-ade57d360e0d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003edkar chag ’phang thang ma\u003c/em\u003e. Beijing: mi rigs dpe skrun khang, 2003.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"7a0e3048-773c-4037-bb80-c7651451041d\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eEimer, Helmut. \u003cem\u003eDer Tantra-Katalog des Bu ston im Vergleich mit der Abteilung Tantra des tibetischen Kanjur: Studie, Textausgabe, Konkordanzen und Indices\u003c/em\u003e. Bonn: Indica et Tibetica Verlag, 1989.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"da27eb8f-1e7c-4ff8-adec-599fc61ea3a8\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eLancaster, Lewis R. \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"http://www.acmuller.net/descriptive_catalogue/index.html\\\"\u003eThe Korean Buddhist Canon\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e. Accessed April 23, 2019.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"03601313-6748-48d3-b7cc-a88884016aaf\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eYoshimura, Shyuki. \u003cem\u003eThe Denkar-Ma: An Oldest Catalogue of the Tibetan Buddhist Canons\u003c/em\u003e. Kyoto: Ryukoku University, 1950.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Secondary Sources\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"5674c733-cab3-4973-8f9c-586e3b40bee1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e84000 Translation Team, trans. \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh505.html\\\"\u003eThe Vaiḍūryaprabha Dhāraṇī\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eVaiḍūrya­prabha­dharaṇī\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 505). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2024.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"3966e84b-2cc0-4cb4-8e1c-fecd7af13337\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDalton, Catherine. trans. \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh505a.html\\\"\u003eA Mantra for Incanting Medicines When Administering Them\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003esman gtong ba’i tshe sman la sngags kyi gdab pa\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 505a). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2023.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"6a72ac5d-33d5-42b2-9ae2-5367bd715d1c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eDharmachakra Translations Committee, trans. \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh503.html\\\"\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Seven Thus-Gone Ones\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (\u003cem\u003eSapta­tathāgata­pūrva­praṇidhāna­viśeṣa­vistāra\u003c/em\u003e, Toh 503). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2021.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]}],\"endnotes\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6f72c638-5cdd-4069-b4f9-f08b3b4fb413\",\"sort\":1221,\"type\":\"endnotesHeader\",\"label\":\"n.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":5,\"uuid\":\"fc41f12a-d87a-46a3-9e58-7b3849bc041f\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8d2fcc1c-7299-4849-873a-6072a418d633\",\"sort\":1223,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.1\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"This sūtra survives in Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan. In Sanskrit, there are three available editions, compiled and edited from the cache of Buddhist Sanskrit manuscripts excavated from a stūpa in Gilgit in the early twentieth century. Gregory Schopen notes that at least five manuscripts of this text were found among the Gilgit collection, and his analysis of them shows that there were at least two distinct recensions of the text circulating in Gilgit during the fifth and sixth centuries ᴄᴇ. Some substantial passages in Sanskrit have also survived as several citations in Śāntideva’s (685–783 ᴄᴇ) Śikṣāsamuccaya, indicating that the text continued to be well known in the Buddhist heartland of India in the eighth century ᴄᴇ.\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":98,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d32721b2-eb27-4f32-b023-fae16259e4e1\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19,\"uuid\":\"8d2fcc1c-7299-4849-873a-6072a418d633\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Schopen 1978, p. 1.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c3f13690-ab6b-4aa2-bde7-2cd06e7a9446\",\"sort\":1225,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.2\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"This sūtra survives in Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan. In Sanskrit, there are three available editions, compiled and edited from the cache of Buddhist Sanskrit manuscripts excavated from a stūpa in Gilgit in the early twentieth century. Gregory Schopen notes that at least five manuscripts of this text were found among the Gilgit collection, and his analysis of them shows that there were at least two distinct recensions of the text circulating in Gilgit during the fifth and sixth centuries ᴄᴇ. Some substantial passages in Sanskrit have also survived as several citations in Śāntideva’s (685–783 ᴄᴇ) Śikṣāsamuccaya, indicating that the text continued to be well known in the Buddhist heartland of India in the eighth century ᴄᴇ.\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":98,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d32721b2-eb27-4f32-b023-fae16259e4e1\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"c3f13690-ab6b-4aa2-bde7-2cd06e7a9446\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Schopen 1978, p. 22.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"aedf591b-688f-4673-8b78-95d8c5ff2fe0\",\"sort\":1227,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.3\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"This sūtra survives in Sanskrit, Chinese, and Tibetan. In Sanskrit, there are three available editions, compiled and edited from the cache of Buddhist Sanskrit manuscripts excavated from a stūpa in Gilgit in the early twentieth century. Gregory Schopen notes that at least five manuscripts of this text were found among the Gilgit collection, and his analysis of them shows that there were at least two distinct recensions of the text circulating in Gilgit during the fifth and sixth centuries ᴄᴇ. Some substantial passages in Sanskrit have also survived as several citations in Śāntideva’s (685–783 ᴄᴇ) Śikṣāsamuccaya, indicating that the text continued to be well known in the Buddhist heartland of India in the eighth century ᴄᴇ.\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":98,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"d32721b2-eb27-4f32-b023-fae16259e4e1\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-9\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":285,\"uuid\":\"aedf591b-688f-4673-8b78-95d8c5ff2fe0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The passages quoted and their location in the present translation are indicated in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":83}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.19,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":88},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a758b1e8-9c61-40d0-b860-661a2a3bbebc\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/8670d6af-5681-4b5c-bc48-174bfa649595\",\"entity\":\"8670d6af-5681-4b5c-bc48-174bfa649595\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":89}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.21,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":89,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b83c0a86-7b4a-4559-883a-1bdef3de855a\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/7da88841-dbf6-4a6d-aa91-d5688fb9f912\",\"entity\":\"7da88841-dbf6-4a6d-aa91-d5688fb9f912\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":99}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.24.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":99,\"end\":104},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"61ff5626-ee92-46f8-8149-18972b5fb41b\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/6c5bfd5c-7350-40c3-8ecc-de8568616b8b\",\"entity\":\"6c5bfd5c-7350-40c3-8ecc-de8568616b8b\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" One passage quoted in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":131}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":131,\"end\":146},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"56ae3a6f-0ae1-430b-ae47-efff3ceef8cd\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(Bendall 1902, p. 13) does not seem to be present in the text, at least not in this version of it. See also Schopen 1978, pp. 26 and 126–7.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":146,\"end\":285}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"26a444a7-34fb-450d-b533-7cdaf8649719\",\"sort\":1237,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.4\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Considerably earlier even than the Sanskrit manuscripts of Gilgit, however, a Chinese translation very similar to the later versions of the text was included as the twelfth and final fascicle of a longer work (Taishō 1331) translated by Śrīmitra in the early fourth century ᴄᴇ. In the seventh century, two new standalone Chinese translations were made, one in 616 ᴄᴇ by Dharmagupta (Taishō 449) and one in 650 ᴄᴇ by Xuanzang (Taishō 450).\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":116,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"9d46234f-6007-492c-b8a4-e34dd7568bd1\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":306,\"uuid\":\"26a444a7-34fb-450d-b533-7cdaf8649719\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Foshuo guanding jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f51c00d3-ef78-49ae-bbcb-398528bda0f4\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(佛說灌頂經, “The Sūtra on Empowerments,” Taishō 1331), whose twelfth fascicle has the subtitle \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":112}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Foshuo guanding ba chu guo zuisheng si de du jing juan dishi er \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":112,\"end\":176},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4e1fc182-92ea-4cb8-ac0b-72c15dfa7792\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(佛說灌頂拔除過罪生死得度經卷第十二, “Section 12, The Sūtra on the Empowerment that Uproots Misdeeds and Achieves Liberation from Life and Death”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":176,\"end\":306}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d5075fb7-80e1-4a33-bd0e-a204fe72eb28\",\"sort\":1246,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.5\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Considerably earlier even than the Sanskrit manuscripts of Gilgit, however, a Chinese translation very similar to the later versions of the text was included as the twelfth and final fascicle of a longer work (Taishō 1331) translated by Śrīmitra in the early fourth century ᴄᴇ. In the seventh century, two new standalone Chinese translations were made, one in 616 ᴄᴇ by Dharmagupta (Taishō 449) and one in 650 ᴄᴇ by Xuanzang (Taishō 450).\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"sort\":116,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"9d46234f-6007-492c-b8a4-e34dd7568bd1\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-13\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":239,\"uuid\":\"d5075fb7-80e1-4a33-bd0e-a204fe72eb28\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yaoshi rulai benyuan jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5845c81c-7b1e-4136-91e1-79be96a26df8\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(佛說藥師如來本願經, Taishō 449), and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yaoshi liuli guang rulai benyuan gongde jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":100},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4da7a05d-d3e5-451f-ae30-844ae900e85e\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(藥師琉璃光如來本願功德經, Taishō 450). For more on the Chinese translations, see Lancaster, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":181}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Korean Buddhist Canon,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":181,\"end\":207},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6095cd7f-5680-4517-8411-7395950d4725\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":207,\"end\":208}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"K 176\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":208,\"end\":213},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"http://www.acmuller.net/descriptive_catalogue/files/k0176.html\",\"uuid\":\"3786f4ca-5c54-44d9-bf6b-5b37a1dac3bf\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":213,\"end\":218}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"K 177\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":218,\"end\":223},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"link\",\"attrs\":{\"href\":\"http://www.acmuller.net/descriptive_catalogue/files/k0177.html\",\"uuid\":\"8a56a3c0-5b36-4a66-a7de-e207fdd58931\",\"type\":\"link\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". See also \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":223,\"end\":234}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"n.10.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":234,\"end\":239},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"558ded00-2daf-4685-a7fa-338510271b74\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/4d572cc8-c0c4-4070-bf14-1304471a04b7\",\"entity\":\"4d572cc8-c0c4-4070-bf14-1304471a04b7\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"endnotes\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a84cc84a-8eb2-42bd-ab57-7c8db17aab93\",\"sort\":1263,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.6\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$20\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"a84cc84a-8eb2-42bd-ab57-7c8db17aab93\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Degé \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkar chag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"981da66a-e6b7-476c-99ea-07877d356cae\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" also mentions Śīlendrabodhi in addition to these translators.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":80}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bf105cac-1915-4a72-9fd8-cf0e2b77482f\",\"sort\":1267,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.7\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$21\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20,\"uuid\":\"bf105cac-1915-4a72-9fd8-cf0e2b77482f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yoshimura 1950, 131.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":20}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9ed1e74c-9752-4d91-90d2-1cd8e24b057f\",\"sort\":1269,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.8\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$22\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35,\"uuid\":\"9ed1e74c-9752-4d91-90d2-1cd8e24b057f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkar chag ’phang thang ma \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":26},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"85e1ae61-563d-4e3c-bf78-db29b7e9eb75\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2003, 11.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":26,\"end\":35}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7b0371ab-a2dc-431b-9660-e8e752f67a09\",\"sort\":1272,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.9\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$23\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":58,\"uuid\":\"7b0371ab-a2dc-431b-9660-e8e752f67a09\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See his \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"chos ’byung \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":20},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ffbcc88d-0f84-4d02-afa6-fef6a0ba3bdc\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"F.152.b; and Eimer 1989, text no. 134.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":20,\"end\":58}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4d572cc8-c0c4-4070-bf14-1304471a04b7\",\"sort\":1276,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.10\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$24\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":184,\"uuid\":\"4d572cc8-c0c4-4070-bf14-1304471a04b7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dharmachakra Translation Committee, 2021\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":44},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5453cf0a-8aa9-4d19-b0cb-379f34dc6cbd\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/bc6cc1d7-f6f4-44b5-98df-0671c52b2121\",\"entity\":\"bc6cc1d7-f6f4-44b5-98df-0671c52b2121\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh503\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This text was also translated into Chinese in 707 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":44,\"end\":96}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":98},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":98,\"uuid\":\"85cb9643-3630-4046-8a8e-a5c81aeb7385\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" by Yijing as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":112}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Yaoshi liuli guang qi fo benyuan gongde jing \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":112,\"end\":157},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"10e21ba7-ce4b-4124-b51f-a0c2dff7e1cc\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"(藥師琉璃光七佛本願功德經, Taishō 451).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":184}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d69e5090-094f-488a-b290-53c33367d6db\",\"sort\":1286,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.11\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$25\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"sort\":129,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"18ad46b6-2ed3-4f76-bc94-cc14f99d50f2\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-301\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"d69e5090-094f-488a-b290-53c33367d6db\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"See \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"i.6 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":8},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"71e47aba-2440-4a9e-bf7f-5feffd7cdca7\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/d32721b2-eb27-4f32-b023-fae16259e4e1\",\"entity\":\"d32721b2-eb27-4f32-b023-fae16259e4e1\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"introduction\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":12}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"i.7.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":16},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dfa8fa2c-9a03-490e-834f-e61c5b0e7420\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/9d46234f-6007-492c-b8a4-e34dd7568bd1\",\"entity\":\"9d46234f-6007-492c-b8a4-e34dd7568bd1\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"introduction\"}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"099c87e9-9a7c-4388-9a82-552efdfbf7a3\",\"sort\":1292,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.12\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$26\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"sort\":161,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"e187c876-f33b-41c6-a494-50c6ecb8e9fa\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-18\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":119,\"uuid\":\"099c87e9-9a7c-4388-9a82-552efdfbf7a3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"84000 Translation Team. trans., \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Vaiḍūryaprabha Dhāraṇī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":58},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"39394b62-9d4a-4f6e-a1ab-408438104d70\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":32,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bb7ddcbd-9735-4c79-9f64-3005363d1d01\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/dc57ca8a-da2f-4772-97b1-d85816e0295c\",\"entity\":\"dc57ca8a-da2f-4772-97b1-d85816e0295c\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh505\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":59},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"39394b62-9d4a-4f6e-a1ab-408438104d70\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":58,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 505 (84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2024).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":119}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9f928597-f0c9-44ef-9eb7-ef43ab6f9fc8\",\"sort\":1296,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.13\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$27\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"sort\":161,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"e187c876-f33b-41c6-a494-50c6ecb8e9fa\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-18\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":145,\"uuid\":\"9f928597-f0c9-44ef-9eb7-ef43ab6f9fc8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dalton, Catherine. trans., \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":27}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"A Mantra for Incanting Medicines When Administering Them\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":27,\"end\":83},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23a0947f-810c-441a-9241-86a556852147\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":27,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bae4f6e6-e72d-42bd-b0fd-4758cc0bcfcc\",\"href\":\"/entity/work/0286e3d2-8ff4-4ec9-b64d-e275dc9d4952\",\"entity\":\"0286e3d2-8ff4-4ec9-b64d-e275dc9d4952\",\"type\":\"work\",\"toh\":null,\"linkToh\":\"toh505a\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":83,\"end\":84},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"23a0947f-810c-441a-9241-86a556852147\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":83,\"end\":0}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Toh 505a (84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2023).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":145}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"632ef2b3-af44-4417-adc2-ab22b5f61d94\",\"sort\":1300,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.14\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Thus did I hear at one time. The Blessed One was wandering through the provinces and came to Vaiśālī. There in Vaiśālī, at the base of the musical tree, he was accompanied by a great saṅgha of eight thousand monks, and with him, too, were thirty-six thousand bodhisattvas and all manner of kings, ministers, brahmins, householders, gods, asuras, garuḍas, kinnaras, and mahoragas, all of whom encircled and venerated him as he taught the Dharma.\",\"label\":\"1.2\",\"sort\":193,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"b4168cba-4b75-48cd-bf42-97c3c0dc677d\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-21\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":247,\"uuid\":\"632ef2b3-af44-4417-adc2-ab22b5f61d94\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tib.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" rol mo’i sgra can gyi shing ljon pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":40},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":40,\"uuid\":\"3213d9d8-d9ff-4ab4-95b3-dc5f04ad3daf\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":47}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vādya­svara­vṛkṣa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":64},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":64,\"uuid\":\"2331bf7d-f145-4ac6-83fa-1654542faa9b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The corresponding term in the Chinese translation of this text is 樂音樹 (Chi. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":142}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yue yin shu\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":142,\"end\":153},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":142,\"end\":153,\"uuid\":\"d5e583ee-8d50-40c6-8a1d-2aadb00f4714\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":153,\"end\":156}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"musical tree\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":156,\"end\":168},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"a5150d0b-1631-40bb-9954-e296550132fa\",\"uuid\":\"d692972c-1726-495e-87cc-c043c330ea39\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”), a term that is commonly used to describe the trees in Amitābha’s pure land.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":168,\"end\":247}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bede20da-070a-4b5e-89b4-2d48d3f9bf31\",\"sort\":1312,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.15\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“May the Blessed One please teach a detailed account of the names and previous aspirations of the thus-gone ones, so that beings who hear them may be purified of their karmic obscurations and be guided, later in future times when only an imitation of the holy Dharma remains.”\",\"label\":\"1.4\",\"sort\":225,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"d238ae70-f15b-4554-a7c2-c7a2de99d9a3\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-24\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":56,\"uuid\":\"bede20da-070a-4b5e-89b4-2d48d3f9bf31\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V, G: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vayam śrutvā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"79b6fd94-5751-4761-b35d-04364a1a9a1a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":21}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":22},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":21,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"4d6695db-a33e-4ac9-916c-7d49b33f4050\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":24}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"taṃ śrutvā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":34},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":24,\"end\":34,\"uuid\":\"1fe44f12-6870-4819-94cc-f80af7739dca\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; Tib.: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gang thos pas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":55},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":55,\"uuid\":\"4f0ee5d7-6f6e-4d4f-83b9-745f2594a0c5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":56}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9a67c48d-ef45-4231-b6a2-535266959f4d\",\"sort\":1322,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.16\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Blessed One continued to address Mañjuśrīkumārabhūta, saying, “Mañjuśrī, there are ordinary beings who do not know about virtue and nonvirtue. They are overcome by greed and do not understand generosity and the ripened result of generosity. They are childish and foolish, lacking the capacity for faith. As they strive to accumulate and maintain wealth, their minds are not disposed toward generosity and sharing. When it is time to give a gift, they become dejected as if they were cutting the flesh from their own bodies. Many of those beings do not even allow themselves to enjoy material wealth, let alone provide for their parents, wives, sons, and daughters, for their male and female servants and employees, and for beggars.\",\"label\":\"1.23\",\"sort\":495,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"72d7eb1d-0202-4cb5-9ca0-0ac4eb60d5da\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-44\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":340,\"uuid\":\"9a67c48d-ef45-4231-b6a2-535266959f4d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"D, S, N, H: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sems can de dag ni bdag nyid kyang du ma yongs su mi spyod na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":73},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"c9a4f8db-8353-442b-b159-36bedd24f5c6\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; V: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":73,\"end\":78}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aneke ca sattvāḥ ye svayameva na paribhuñjanti\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":124},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":124,\"uuid\":\"37f82333-555d-40d8-be8c-4f5fff0e4f5a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; G: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":124,\"end\":129}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aneke ca sattvā ye svayameva na paribhuñjanti\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":129,\"end\":174},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":129,\"end\":174,\"uuid\":\"133ce45f-0498-47f5-b576-c362aae8a247\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":174,\"end\":177}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":178},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":177,\"end\":178,\"uuid\":\"9948b703-6820-418a-8cf0-d755326af881\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":178,\"end\":180}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aneke ca te satttvā ye svayam evātmana na paribhuṃjanti\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":180,\"end\":235},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":180,\"end\":235,\"uuid\":\"d85dcbc9-2fb5-4959-8513-a3aa8357e180\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit suggests that the Tibetan term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":235,\"end\":281}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"du ma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":286},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":286,\"uuid\":\"bb3be00e-d26d-4685-97ae-5835508f58eb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":286,\"end\":293}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"aneke\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":293,\"end\":298},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":293,\"end\":298,\"uuid\":\"450957d5-5d01-4b76-801e-017d0083f910\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") modifies \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":298,\"end\":309}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sems can de dag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":309,\"end\":324},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":309,\"end\":324,\"uuid\":\"49214268-53fd-4869-bb05-c893adf34a74\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":324,\"end\":331}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sattvāḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":331,\"end\":338},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":331,\"end\":338,\"uuid\":\"6bc1ee28-0e4c-4e8f-9d88-238d3cd8abfe\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":338,\"end\":340}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b1606971-b954-46c6-aebb-44cfb3d53775\",\"sort\":1342,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.17\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Moreover, Mañjuśrī, there are beings who undermine the precepts of the thus-gone ones, violating discipline and engaging in wrong views. There are those who are disciplined and may maintain their discipline, but do not seek erudition, and so do not understand the profound meaning of the discourses that the Thus-Gone One has taught. There are those who do become erudite but develop excessive pride, and because they are overcome by their pride, they act with jealousy toward others and misuse and forsake the holy Dharma. Such foolish people who side with Māra pursue a bad path themselves and cause many billions of other beings to fall into the great abyss. Those beings are reborn amidst the horrors of hell.\",\"label\":\"1.25\",\"sort\":529,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7b7cbdcf-2792-415c-b157-96dd2fd6cb6c\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-47\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":159,\"uuid\":\"b1606971-b954-46c6-aebb-44cfb3d53775\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 503 here reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":19}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bslab pa’i gnas ’dzin pa dag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"f97a543a-6783-4f90-b2fc-801e5ca3eb9b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“beings who hold the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":70}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"precepts\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":78},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e1894c5d-a0ba-4881-b9aa-06595e73a72a\",\"uuid\":\"ce5e8ff3-35c7-4b19-b26b-7dc81fe48994\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”) rather than \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":78,\"end\":93}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bslab pa’i gnas ’jig pa dag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":120},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":120,\"uuid\":\"8686ad32-1cc2-4f3c-a1d8-cf48d81d5431\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“beings who undermine the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":148}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"precepts\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":156},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"e1894c5d-a0ba-4881-b9aa-06595e73a72a\",\"uuid\":\"ca0a290f-20a2-41a3-be9d-ae517a209667\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":156,\"end\":159}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f586d37e-6bcb-467d-ba43-a537890390aa\",\"sort\":1352,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.18\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Those who have heard the name of the blessed, thus-gone, worthy, and perfect Buddha Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha in a previous life as a human being will be liberated from all manner of suffering due to that root of virtue. They will be intelligent, learned, bright, prudent, and focused on pursuing virtue, and they will always find company with a spiritual teacher. They will cut Māra’s bonds, crush the eggshell of ignorance, and dry up the river of the afflictions. They will be liberated from birth, old age, death, anguish, lamentation, suffering, unhappiness, and conflict.\",\"label\":\"1.28\",\"sort\":567,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"defa47ce-9eeb-447a-8dad-4e92e87d230a\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-51\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":412,\"uuid\":\"f586d37e-6bcb-467d-ba43-a537890390aa\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsal ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":12},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":12,\"uuid\":\"cc310a98-bccb-4dd0-9f4a-4da24f5747fc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; Skt. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":12,\"end\":19}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vyakta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":25},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":19,\"end\":25,\"uuid\":\"486a9f55-a4e5-45da-91d0-8de6f3263cf2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":40}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vyakta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":46},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":46,\"uuid\":\"20cc072e-6b70-4d69-9746-5170f2256973\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" comes from \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":46,\"end\":58}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vyañj\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":63},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":58,\"end\":63,\"uuid\":\"ba808d31-db9a-459c-9344-fb0ed5afceb0\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", which means “to make evident.” Thus \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":101}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vyakta\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":107},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":101,\"end\":107,\"uuid\":\"f2cc58a4-26f6-4a56-a79f-2bd783a7e5d2\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" carries the sense of “clear,” “apparent,” “evident,” which is close to what we mean in English when we say that someone is “bright,” meaning that for them things are clear and evident and that they have the ability to make other things apparent or evident, just as a light makes things clear and evident.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":107,\"end\":412}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8670d6af-5681-4b5c-bc48-174bfa649595\",\"sort\":1364,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.19\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Others will be born in great kṣatriya households, born in great brahmin households, born in great landowning households, and born in households whose treasuries and storehouses contain an abundance of riches and grain. They will have excellent physiques, be powerful, have attendants, be courageous and heroic, and have the strength of a great champion. Any woman who should hear the Thus-Gone One’s name and bear it in mind should know that it is the last time she will be of the female gender.”\",\"label\":\"1.32\",\"sort\":637,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"e096316c-b8ba-4d35-8c1d-b6823578cebc\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-56\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":101,\"uuid\":\"8670d6af-5681-4b5c-bc48-174bfa649595\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The three paragraphs ending with this one are quoted in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya;\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":75},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0b498ad9-0488-4f97-a6fa-1a23c90bb4ab\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" see Bendall 1902, p. 175.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":101}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"32a15946-a6a2-408a-9cbf-96baca4328a4\",\"sort\":1368,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.20\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“If those who face dangers from fire, dangers from water, dangers from weapons, dangers from poison, dangers from steep cliffs, dangers from raging elephants, dangers from lions, dangers from tigers, dangers from bears, hyenas, and poisonous snakes, and dangers from snakes, scorpions, and centipedes, have made offerings to that thus-gone one, they will be freed from all manner of dangers. Those who face dangers from enemy armies, dangers from thieves, and dangers from bandits should also make offerings to that thus-gone one.\",\"label\":\"1.38\",\"sort\":726,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7f535eaf-9af0-43dd-a4db-cc06495ec0f9\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-63\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"32a15946-a6a2-408a-9cbf-96baca4328a4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"D, S: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mchod pa byas na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":22},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":22,\"uuid\":\"38619193-0f8a-4b4c-9fc0-64a92a11d00f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; V, G, S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":31}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":32},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":32,\"uuid\":\"5bd9f902-d032-48aa-995a-591fa5cd452b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":34}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"pūjā kartavyā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"c9da5ec1-2f1d-4f2a-ae63-0ed1dd247418\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":48}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7da88841-dbf6-4a6d-aa91-d5688fb9f912\",\"sort\":1376,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Moreover, Mañjuśrī, if any faithful sons or daughters of good family who maintain taking refuge in the Three Jewels for as long as they live and have no other tutelary deity, maintain the five precepts, maintain the ten precepts, maintain the four hundred vows and precepts of a bodhisattva, are monks who have left home and maintain the two hundred and fifty precepts, or are nuns who maintain the five hundred precepts, should break any one of the precepts among the vows and precepts they have taken and fear they are in danger of falling into the lower realms, if they then make offerings to the blessed Thus-Gone One Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha, they should know that they will not suffer rebirth in the three lower realms.\",\"label\":\"1.39\",\"sort\":742,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"8d07f68b-9351-49ca-8936-72f30cb06097\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-65\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":73,\"uuid\":\"7da88841-dbf6-4a6d-aa91-d5688fb9f912\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This paragraph is quoted in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya;\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":32,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4006c931-a64d-4124-97a6-64be2879ffed\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" see Bendall 1902, p. 174.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":73}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2cb6d8da-147e-4384-9913-9a92f6300dc8\",\"sort\":1380,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.22\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Respected Blessed One,” Venerable Ānanda replied, “I am not uncertain, nor do I have any reservations or doubts about the qualities that the Thus-Gone One has described, because the thus-gone ones have no impure conduct of body, speech, and mind. Blessed One, even such miraculous and powerful beings as the sun and the moon might fall to the earth, and even Sumeru, the king of mountains, might move from its base, but the word of the buddhas is never incorrect. Yet still, respected Blessed One, there are beings who lack the capacity for faith, and when they hear about this buddha domain of the buddhas they will wonder, ‘How can such good qualities and benefits come about by merely recollecting the name of that thus-gone one?’ Because they have no faith, do not believe, and reject this, for a long time they will suffer injuries, lack medicines, be unhappy, and fall into the lower realms.”\",\"label\":\"1.42\",\"sort\":796,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9da693e5-9e9b-415f-ad90-d4289a5b32b5\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-69\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":264,\"uuid\":\"2cb6d8da-147e-4384-9913-9a92f6300dc8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V, G, S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":8},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":8,\"uuid\":\"1ee853b3-1446-4172-9a04-895dc930cc65\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"idaṃ buddha­gocaraṃ śrutvā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":36},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":36,\"uuid\":\"37f799e1-68a4-48cd-99d3-63c5f86a5815\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; D: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":36,\"end\":41}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sangs rgyas rnams kyi sangs rgyas kyi spyod yul ’di thos na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":100},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":100,\"uuid\":\"e2a035dc-5f1e-46a9-b0e6-f32e97ec99cc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S, Y, K: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":100,\"end\":111}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sangs rgyas rnams kyi sangs rgyas kyis spyod yul ’di thos na\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":171},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":111,\"end\":171,\"uuid\":\"82250225-e0b1-4b71-83ec-ecb49d5899c1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The translation follows the Sanskrit editions of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":171,\"end\":226}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­sūtra \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":226,\"end\":247},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4a20eaed-1cee-4c88-b490-55d67358cb3f\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"in this instance.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":247,\"end\":264}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4456bc11-be25-43db-921a-dce52bae1b05\",\"sort\":1392,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.23\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Blessed One replied, “Ānanda, it is untenable and impossible for someone who has had the name of that thus-gone one resound in their ears to be reborn in the lower realms. Ānanda, the domain of the buddhas is difficult to believe. Ānanda, the faith and belief you have should be seen as the power of the Thus-Gone One. This is something possessed only by bodhisattva great beings who are one birth away from awakening‍—not by hearers and solitary buddhas.\",\"label\":\"1.43\",\"sort\":824,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"30ab4572-741d-4da5-941c-3480f97f731d\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-71\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":91,\"uuid\":\"4456bc11-be25-43db-921a-dce52bae1b05\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V, G, S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":8},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":7,\"end\":8,\"uuid\":\"d255c03b-5853-4f03-9660-82896babd142\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgatasyaiṣo ’nubhāvo draṣṭavyaḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":45},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":45,\"uuid\":\"6eacbc7e-d169-44e2-809c-4de22389ddb3\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; D: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"de bzhin gshegs pa’i mthu yin par blta’o\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":90},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":90,\"uuid\":\"aef0d6d0-7fb3-4581-8a40-1753435a724f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":90,\"end\":91}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"6c5bfd5c-7350-40c3-8ecc-de8568616b8b\",\"sort\":1400,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.24\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Blessed One replied, “Ānanda, it is untenable and impossible for someone who has had the name of that thus-gone one resound in their ears to be reborn in the lower realms. Ānanda, the domain of the buddhas is difficult to believe. Ānanda, the faith and belief you have should be seen as the power of the Thus-Gone One. This is something possessed only by bodhisattva great beings who are one birth away from awakening‍—not by hearers and solitary buddhas.\",\"label\":\"1.43\",\"sort\":824,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"30ab4572-741d-4da5-941c-3480f97f731d\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-71\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":104,\"uuid\":\"6c5bfd5c-7350-40c3-8ecc-de8568616b8b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The three paragraphs ending with this one are quoted in the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śikṣāsamuccaya;\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":75},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e010daf2-5a40-4a9f-bd86-5d0a49c10baa\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" see Bendall 1902, pp. 174–5.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":75,\"end\":104}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ff9df9e9-ac3b-4a2a-a453-e64cefc0a735\",\"sort\":1404,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.25\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“While such a person’s body is still lying there, the consciousness will be brought before the Dharma King Yama. The god who was born with that person and who has recorded all of that person’s virtuous and nonvirtuous actions in writing will then present them to the Dharma King Yama. The Dharma King Yama will then question and interrogate the person and issue his judgment based on how many of their actions were virtuous and how many were nonvirtuous.\",\"label\":\"1.46\",\"sort\":885,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3f5abdf1-2564-43dd-91a9-39782b8c32af\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-76\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":123,\"uuid\":\"ff9df9e9-ac3b-4a2a-a453-e64cefc0a735\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tib: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mi de dang lhan cig skyes pa’i lha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":39},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":5,\"end\":39,\"uuid\":\"11f0f33b-a525-4c8c-bc7f-f34cd8418903\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":43},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"2d7a0521-68e1-44b2-baf3-77ac2568e0d5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":45}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"puruṣasya sahajā pṛṣṭ[h]ānubaddha devatā\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":85},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":45,\"end\":85,\"uuid\":\"86cf8066-728e-415e-b20c-eefbbacc6ce5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; G, V: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":93}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sattvasya sahajānubaddham eva\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":122},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":93,\"end\":122,\"uuid\":\"f5d76bce-7db5-40de-a1c9-f4098731fdc8\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":122,\"end\":123}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a19214cb-2621-4a22-a161-60a6ab348119\",\"sort\":1414,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.26\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“If the friends, acquaintances, and relatives of those who are ill take refuge in the blessed Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja and perform the offering in this way to benefit them, their consciousness will turn back and make its way, just as if they had been dreaming, to the place where they had been. For some the consciousness will return on the seventh day, for some on the twenty-first, thirty-fifth, or forty-ninth day, and they will remember what happened to them. The ripening of virtuous and nonvirtuous actions will now be clear to them, and they will no longer commit unwholesome actions, even at the expense of their life. Therefore, faithful sons or daughters of good family should make offerings to that thus-gone one.”\",\"label\":\"1.47\",\"sort\":898,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c646609e-5679-4e14-a4f3-a69cad97af6d\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-78\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":174,\"uuid\":\"a19214cb-2621-4a22-a161-60a6ab348119\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V, G: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tatra ye te mitrajnātisālohitāḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"6d415a8b-3d62-4762-a856-12528a4e25e5\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":40}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":41},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"99f5ccd7-a641-4b63-83cb-83256cb7fe95\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\": \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ye tasya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":51},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"8bf6f1f1-24b3-4af0-a6a6-e5bf8b30a4ef\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Tibetan does not provide the subject here, so our translation supplies it from the Vaidya and Dutt Sanskrit editions.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":174}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"1346a21b-1809-4e65-9e44-c30bb690d455\",\"sort\":1422,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.27\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“If the friends, acquaintances, and relatives of those who are ill take refuge in the blessed Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja and perform the offering in this way to benefit them, their consciousness will turn back and make its way, just as if they had been dreaming, to the place where they had been. For some the consciousness will return on the seventh day, for some on the twenty-first, thirty-fifth, or forty-ninth day, and they will remember what happened to them. The ripening of virtuous and nonvirtuous actions will now be clear to them, and they will no longer commit unwholesome actions, even at the expense of their life. Therefore, faithful sons or daughters of good family should make offerings to that thus-gone one.”\",\"label\":\"1.47\",\"sort\":898,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"c646609e-5679-4e14-a4f3-a69cad97af6d\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-78\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":408,\"uuid\":\"1346a21b-1809-4e65-9e44-c30bb690d455\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This passage has been taken as referring to revival after actual death or, alternatively, to recovery from coma or near-death. The paradox of designating as having actually died someone who is subsequently revived is no doubt part of what underlies \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":249}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Ānanda\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":249,\"end\":255},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b35041f2-96b8-4d55-b39a-9d0653dffcd6\",\"uuid\":\"f9ed3b07-dae9-468c-ad4b-897dc2c3ae88\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s question below, in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":255,\"end\":277}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1.51,\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":277,\"end\":282},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"internalLink\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"39ee2cf8-6ce3-4d63-be79-4b4eddffd372\",\"href\":\"/entity/passage/94c683f7-ec48-4575-9548-a9c3f29d3290\",\"entity\":\"94c683f7-ec48-4575-9548-a9c3f29d3290\",\"type\":\"passage\",\"toh\":null,\"isSameWork\":true,\"subtype\":\"translation\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and in the passage on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":282,\"end\":305}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"untimely death\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":305,\"end\":319},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"ab2e041a-4033-4bfa-8d05-9b343f2ac529\",\"uuid\":\"cc8832d8-5756-43dc-a519-aa2fbf1e711a\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" that follows. For a discussion of different interpretations see Schopen 1978, pp. 354–7.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":319,\"end\":408}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d98deaa7-a5c6-41a9-b500-5936472c1a2f\",\"sort\":1430,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.28\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"$28\",\"label\":\"1.50\",\"sort\":946,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9a6b4173-d6c4-44ed-afda-7da7526c76ee\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-82\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":208,\"uuid\":\"d98deaa7-a5c6-41a9-b500-5936472c1a2f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Both the Sanskrit and the Tibetan texts switch here to “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":56}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kṣatriya\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":64},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"d64414dc-ad29-4e9d-99b1-d700901d25ab\",\"uuid\":\"5fd80d01-e48a-4010-b063-d3804ec95eb3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" king” in the singular. The English translation reads this in the plural to maintain proper subject agreement in number throughout this section.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":64,\"end\":208}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cbbf0433-7d8c-402c-bdf1-96051c2aad18\",\"sort\":1434,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.29\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There were twelve great yakṣa generals gathered in that assembly‍—the great yakṣa general Kiṃbhīra, the great yakṣa general Vajra, the great yakṣa general Mekhila, the great yakṣa general Antila, the great yakṣa general Anila, the great yakṣa general Saṇṭhila, the great yakṣa general Indala, the great yakṣa general Pāyila, the great yakṣa general Mahāla, the great yakṣa general Cidāla, the great yakṣa general Caundhula, and the great yakṣa general Vikala.\",\"label\":\"1.53\",\"sort\":1044,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"a93cf62f-2513-4adf-9c3b-ac637cc973c5\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-86\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":371,\"uuid\":\"cbbf0433-7d8c-402c-bdf1-96051c2aad18\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Some of the names for these \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":28}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yakṣa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":33},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5d1d861a-9a7d-45ee-9d4e-a843c5698e55\",\"uuid\":\"d49d0ae8-e795-4080-8365-1e3ef7c97366\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" generals that are provided in the Sanskrit editions of the text do not seem to be standard Sanskrit and may reflect the preservation of local, vernacular \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":33,\"end\":188}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"yakṣa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":188,\"end\":193},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"5d1d861a-9a7d-45ee-9d4e-a843c5698e55\",\"uuid\":\"394ee34c-6add-4dc9-81d6-1b7e23225f09\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" traditions in the text. The Tibetan renderings for these names, which may in fact offer the proper translation of these nonstandard Sanskrit names, are provided in the glossary.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":193,\"end\":371}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"dc0a6493-d00c-42c7-924c-ea8efc3c63e7\",\"sort\":1440,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.30\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Very good, very good,” the Blessed One said in response to the great yakṣa generals. “It is excellent that you great yakṣa generals are so grateful toward the blessed Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja, and that you are so committed to recollecting him and working for the benefit of all beings.”\",\"label\":\"1.55\",\"sort\":1129,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"2bd895fc-eaeb-455f-affe-4ae6cf32cfa5\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-89\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":215,\"uuid\":\"dc0a6493-d00c-42c7-924c-ea8efc3c63e7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"V, G: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":6}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"kṛtajñatām anusmaramāṇānāṃ sarvasattvānāṃ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":47},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":6,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"70c1b5dc-c530-434b-b36e-f537bb61a914\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":47,\"end\":50}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"C\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":51},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"subscript\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":51,\"uuid\":\"3ecc116b-62e0-49c3-985c-5468996d452b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"subscript\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\":\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":52}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" kṛtajñatām anusmaramāṇaḥ sarvasatvānāṃ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":91},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":52,\"end\":91,\"uuid\":\"7b0cb704-3e15-4074-9aa4-ec43fb5f502a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; D: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":91,\"end\":96}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byas pa g.zo zhing rjes su dran la sems can thams cad la\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":96,\"end\":152,\"uuid\":\"78013d20-d643-4760-b22f-6c41f5cffd8d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; S: \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":157}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"byas pa g.zo zhing rjes su dran la /sems can thams cad la\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":214},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":157,\"end\":214,\"uuid\":\"e3dbd2e8-cb56-4e1c-9dc1-96cbf29e86de\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":214,\"end\":215}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5f481738-1100-4bcf-aae7-21e4e115b1e9\",\"sort\":1452,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.31\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Translated, edited, and finalized according to the new language reform by the Indian preceptors Jinamitra and Dānaśīla along with the chief editor and translator Bandé Yeshé Dé.\",\"label\":\"c.1\",\"sort\":1190,\"type\":\"colophon\",\"uuid\":\"f852a56f-2a48-450a-96ae-c9a5b5356588\",\"workUuid\":\"0305cbcb-6c23-4c7b-83f9-19fc8f07b0b2\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-087-009-95\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"5f481738-1100-4bcf-aae7-21e4e115b1e9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Degé \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":9}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"dkar chag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":18},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":9,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"f4236beb-07e4-4c67-8157-2dfd020569b4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" adds Śīlendrabodhi to the Indian preceptors named here.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":74}}]}]}],\"glossary\":[{\"uuid\":\"7b4e3b42-8510-401e-9185-c65cc0c09cc5\",\"authority\":\"7e3373ba-568b-407e-bf81-43bc00a86b03\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"acquaintance\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉེ་དུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jñāti\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nye du\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ca4d29f6-0a4e-44fe-bd3b-094638f2ef92\",\"authority\":\"3dab101c-dce0-4425-bf7d-5d051add7728\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"aid\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7d8e26c4-d00a-499a-990a-e09d92900f70\",\"authority\":\"46d135e0-0d59-43cd-9955-45a1d1cbb6d8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe buddha who presides over the buddhafield \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-265\\\"\u003eSukhāvatī\u003c/span\u003e; also known as Amitābha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitāyus\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚེ་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitāyus\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshe dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b35041f2-96b8-4d55-b39a-9d0653dffcd6\",\"authority\":\"2c02baf4-0ece-4579-8f66-c49bcc21f21f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Buddha Śākyamuni’s attendant who is celebrated for having recited all the Buddha’s teachings by memory at the first council of the Buddhist saṅgha, thus preserving the Buddha’s teachings after his parinirvāṇa. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ānanda\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་དགའ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ānanda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun dga’ bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"11128676-99d3-4fdb-b630-fb00bd5c832a\",\"authority\":\"a7f12711-6937-40a1-8fb2-5bb6192a8838\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anila\",\"tibetan\":\"རླུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rlung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0e6c3f4b-cbdc-48fe-a677-a38c8e2f68a7\",\"authority\":\"09d9fd7d-92c5-4787-9ac7-94b3af13d10f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Antila\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟའ་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"antila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gza’ ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"447fc7a7-051b-4fc0-b42f-c565f67f73d1\",\"authority\":\"32837dd6-edd0-49d4-b729-9e3e243c4fa1\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA type of nonhuman being whose precise status is subject to different views, but is included as one of the six classes of beings in the sixfold classification of realms of rebirth. In the Buddhist context, asuras are powerful beings said to be dominated by envy, ambition, and hostility. They are also known in the pre-Buddhist and pre-Vedic mythologies of India and Iran, and feature prominently in Vedic and post-Vedic Brahmanical mythology, as well as in the Buddhist tradition. In these traditions, asuras are often described as being engaged in interminable conflict with the devas (gods).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"asura\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ་མ་ཡིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"asura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha ma yin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"715734e9-5f03-4a3e-8bce-d76f45d1b1f2\",\"authority\":\"07a6a5e2-c605-4a1c-b229-1a5b37f71417\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eYeshé Dé (late eighth to early ninth century) was the most prolific translator of sūtras into Tibetan. Altogether he is credited with the translation of more than one hundred sixty sūtra translations and more than one hundred additional translations, mostly on tantric topics. In spite of Yeshé Dé’s great importance for the propagation of Buddhism in Tibet during the imperial era, only a few biographical details about this figure are known. Later sources describe him as a student of the Indian teacher Padmasambhava, and he is also credited with teaching both sūtra and tantra widely to students of his own. He was also known as Nanam Yeshé Dé, from the Nanam (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003esna nam\u003c/em\u003e) clan.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bandé Yeshé Dé\",\"tibetan\":\"བནྡེ་ཡེ་ཤེས་སྡེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ban+de ye shes sde\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4adc3878-7b91-4698-a68b-8b62781a6adc\",\"authority\":\"7a9133fd-f08a-442e-8024-a620f1da3683\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"be restored\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་པར་སྐྱེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhivivardhate\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon par skye\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b38cc372-b545-4778-b427-798edb1137f7\",\"authority\":\"da705bb3-23b1-4f50-9584-adae6e460652\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"beaten\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྡེག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prahāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brdeg pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3ffc011e-faa9-469d-86fa-ce559364f6ca\",\"authority\":\"20ecf869-2842-4b16-917c-a174057be74e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"benevolent\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱམས་པ་ལ་གནས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"maitrīvihāra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byams pa la gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"86c2c568-8ea3-4b91-881b-8d2fe6023691\",\"authority\":\"208361b1-31f1-495d-955d-491fc5f28265\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA short form of the name of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-237\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/span\u003e, the Medicine Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་གྱི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhaiṣajya­guru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman gyi lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"496408c1-e2d7-4787-acaf-cf6b194d9722\",\"authority\":\"919ab19b-e30f-4198-9170-2f8152e5ff29\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Medicine Buddha, the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003ethus-gone one\u003c/span\u003e residing in the buddhafield \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-269\\\"\u003eVaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\u003c/span\u003e. Also called \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-238\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་གྱི་ལྷ་བཻ་ཌཱུརྱའི་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman gyi lha bai DUr+ya’i ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"42700cf7-b80f-42be-89b1-6b4b26f2b60a\",\"authority\":\"86597115-1582-47be-b899-e278b988cd75\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Medicine Buddha, the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003ethus-gone one\u003c/span\u003e residing in the buddhafield \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-269\\\"\u003eVaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\u003c/span\u003e. Also called \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-237\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨན་གྱི་ལྷ་བཻ་ཌཱུརྱའི་འོད་ཀྱི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sman gyi lha bai DUr+ya’i ’od kyi rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"298aea65-db33-4768-b6eb-6be995b4d287\",\"authority\":\"abfb82a4-0572-4b94-86e7-094f955f6922\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThis term in its broadest sense can refer to any being, whether human, animal, or nonhuman. However, it is often used to refer to a specific class of nonhuman beings, especially when bhūtas are mentioned alongside rākṣasas, piśācas, or pretas. In common with these other kinds of nonhumans, bhūtas are usually depicted with unattractive and misshapen bodies. Like several other classes of nonhuman beings, bhūtas take spontaneous birth. As their leader is traditionally regarded to be Rudra-Śiva (also known by the name Bhūta), with whom they haunt dangerous and wild places, bhūtas are especially prominent in Śaivism, where large sections of certain tantras concentrate on them.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bhūta\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྱུང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’byung po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8dca4b02-7b6d-4b86-a1fa-672fa5f90cd0\",\"authority\":\"2b190410-5ef2-4a3a-a428-89d999d14336\",\"definition\":\"$29\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"blessed, blessed one\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhagavat, bhagavān\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bcom ldan ’das\"}},{\"uuid\":\"38e053c9-0710-491c-aa43-54407747fbed\",\"authority\":\"d91c83c5-9e87-4d5f-b17c-c2c74a6193fb\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"blind\",\"tibetan\":\"ལོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"andha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"long ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"10c7e31c-8ab9-4465-a8ba-3027ff390cc4\",\"authority\":\"6e7d97ae-2219-4971-8336-362aa5cfc678\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlthough \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evaiḍūrya\u003c/em\u003e‍—particularly in the context of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-236\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru\u003c/span\u003e‍—has often been translated as lapis lazuli, blue beryl is overall a better match for the descriptions and references in the Sanskrit and Tibetan literature. The equivalent Pāli form of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evaiḍūrya\u003c/em\u003e is \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-pi\\\" lang=\\\"pi-LATN\\\"\u003eveḷuriya\u003c/em\u003e. The Prākrit form \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003everulia\u003c/em\u003e is the source for the English word “beryl.” There are white, yellow, and green beryls (green beryl is generally called “emerald”), but in this case blue beryl needs to be specified to match traditional descriptions. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eVaiḍūrya\u003c/em\u003e may nevertheless have been taken to designate different gems at different times and places, and no single equivalent in English is entirely satisfactory.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"blue beryl\",\"tibetan\":\"བཻ་ཌཱུརྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiḍūrya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bai DUr+ya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"29c40432-a61e-422b-abdf-65eb303e5623\",\"authority\":\"0ad04517-b9d2-4244-a280-e4a36893dc80\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"body\",\"tibetan\":\"ཁོ་ལག, སྐུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kho lag, sku\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1f20fd9f-f11b-41ed-a739-56ca809859d3\",\"authority\":\"e3741278-a4ef-4fc3-be7f-ee5c03a73040\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bound\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅིང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"baddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bcing ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"29f993af-be3f-4744-bb27-4dc0a9e891cc\",\"authority\":\"f710a511-52cd-4e16-8d7d-eaed412fa6e4\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"buddha domain\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་སྤྱོད་ཡུལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"buddhagocara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sangs rgyas kyi spyod yul\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6034a49d-847e-41ad-aae1-7a995b361ec8\",\"authority\":\"228f087d-1e8d-4d2f-81ee-347754a953f0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the two primary bodhisattvas who accompany the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003eThus-Gone One\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-238\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\u003c/span\u003e in the buddhafield \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-269\\\"\u003eVaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Candra­vairocana\",\"tibetan\":\"ཟླ་བ་ལྟེར་རྣམ་པར་སྣང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"candra­vairocana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zla ba lter rnam par snang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"48c4e892-0a3a-468c-a5d5-b7f3dcdd2895\",\"authority\":\"838d0d27-5490-462a-894a-046d6bf6ab63\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Caundhula\",\"tibetan\":\"གཡོ་བ་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caundhula\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"g.yo ba ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"148f89d5-5342-4a4d-ab54-14b440d585be\",\"authority\":\"7cd43603-e2d2-47c1-a59b-0a50a3f2c157\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"centipede\",\"tibetan\":\"རྐང་ལག་བརྒྱ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rkang lag brgya pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b401f8fc-2c49-41d1-8878-e66c0a63dabc\",\"authority\":\"24d098a2-7653-4ec3-b7e6-8db5823132cc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Cidāla\",\"tibetan\":\"བསམ་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cidāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bsam ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"610e43db-e971-495d-ad77-263b0c9b5d6b\",\"authority\":\"5efb9a4e-986f-4897-8bf9-1849d5343d9f\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"crops will be good\",\"tibetan\":\"ལོ་ལེགས་པར་འགྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"subhikṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lo legs par ’gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4b9d0013-a2c6-4bd3-aa1e-602a5297627d\",\"authority\":\"c768392b-e762-4e7e-b4ac-4d59c7bd7632\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn Indian preceptor and translator who lived in the ninth century.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dānaśīla\",\"tibetan\":\"དཱ་ན་ཤཱི་ལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dānaśīla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dA na shI la\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d022c947-1f15-4a5c-a30e-5e5ff55acaad\",\"authority\":\"25b6da1c-51e6-4ca0-bac4-ee067217fd5c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"deaf\",\"tibetan\":\"འོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"badhira\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’on pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ab2e041a-4033-4bfa-8d05-9b343f2ac529\",\"authority\":\"7fc862a2-2435-4f5e-be78-c620fc0884b2\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"death occurring before it is time, untimely death\",\"tibetan\":\"དུས་མ་ཡིན་པར་འཆི་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akālamaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dus ma yin par ’chi ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"54c235ea-276c-48dd-ae08-eae32314a7a1\",\"authority\":\"bc2c8a1b-6799-4a9b-a768-246e085488c3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the three root afflictions that bind beings to cyclic existence. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"desire\",\"tibetan\":\"འདོད་ཆགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rāga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’dod chags\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f2ab8b11-0a86-4371-8a2b-e128f5cd5c89\",\"authority\":\"aecb6201-b278-4eb1-8434-84536faf457a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dishonored\",\"tibetan\":\"ང་རྒྱལ་དང་བྲལ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vimānita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nga rgyal dang bral ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"de2f3c99-801f-408f-9132-c76849331414\",\"authority\":\"15e3b9f3-f86d-42cc-854b-91432dd005d7\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"dumb\",\"tibetan\":\"བེམས་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jaḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bems po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dad2dff9-0c7e-4968-9332-94d4434d4b8e\",\"authority\":\"58a5e000-2bae-4b50-8bba-ab0f39a2ed5e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eight bodhisattvas\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་བརྒྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aṣṭabodhisattva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub sems dpa’ brgyad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5e2c147b-8fd1-47ec-85fd-32a254a33661\",\"authority\":\"cb730ac3-b20e-45ae-a654-fb9acdd02903\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eTo refrain from (1) killing, (2) stealing, (3) sexual activity, (4) false speech, (5) intoxication, (6) singing, dancing, music, and beautifying oneself with adornments or cosmetics, (7) using a high or large bed, and (8) eating at improper times. Typically, this observance is maintained by lay people for twenty-four hours on new moon and full moon days, as well as other special days in the lunar calendar.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eightfold precepts\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡན་ལག་བརྒྱད་པའི་བསྙེན་གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yan lag brgyad pa’i bsnyen gnas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fe7448d9-9209-432f-8696-143f0a36d9cf\",\"authority\":\"69e209c0-8d07-4b75-871c-3a28170d6198\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA set of eighty bodily characteristics and insignia borne by both buddhas and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-221\\\"\u003euniversal emperors\u003c/span\u003e. They are considered “minor” in terms of being secondary to the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-211\\\"\u003ethirty-two marks of a great person\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"eighty minor marks\",\"tibetan\":\"དཔེ་བྱད་བཟང་པོ་བརྒྱད་ཅུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśītyanuvyañjana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dpe byad bzang po brgyad cu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"60722a01-b9ed-4f9a-81b0-1c8aaea06b3f\",\"authority\":\"ee2987ec-95a6-4bf6-80d0-e6d39a48c81f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eFive fundamental \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-194\\\"\u003eprecepts\u003c/span\u003e of abstaining from (1) killing, (2) stealing, (3) sexual misconduct, (4) lying, and (5) intoxication.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"five precepts\",\"tibetan\":\"བསླབ་པའི་གཞི་ལྔ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcaśikṣāpada\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bslab pa’i gzhi lnga po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3c859288-df02-440f-b02c-ccdb20807dcc\",\"authority\":\"5b9bf55c-31be-4f89-be26-2dafde56604d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of spirit being.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"forest deity\",\"tibetan\":\"ནགས་ཚལ་གྱི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vanadevatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nags tshal gyi lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6d3981fe-2fad-444e-8a5a-b21926433e03\",\"authority\":\"d0099514-8ec5-4014-9139-eb47d42c74a0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eFour gods who live on the lower slopes (fourth level) of Mount Meru in the eponymous Heaven of the Four Great Kings (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eCāturmahā­rājika\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ergyal chen bzhi’i ris\u003c/em\u003e) and guard the four cardinal directions. Each is the leader of a nonhuman class of beings living in his realm. They are Dhṛtarāṣṭra, ruling the gandharvas in the east; Virūḍhaka, ruling over the kumbhāṇḍas in the south; Virūpākṣa, ruling the nāgas in the west; and Vaiśravaṇa (also known as Kubera) ruling the yakṣas in the north. Also referred to as Guardians of the World or World Protectors (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003elokapāla\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003e’jig rten skyong ba\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Four Great Kings\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་པོ་ཆེན་པོ་བཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"caturmahārāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal po chen po bzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5498fc5d-cc02-4013-a3af-2e93940bc8f6\",\"authority\":\"74461fd0-5ed8-4923-b6bb-16bb40dfa426\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of generally benevolent nonhuman beings who inhabit the skies, sometimes said to inhabit fantastic cities in the clouds, and more specifically to dwell on the eastern slopes of Mount Meru, where they are ruled by the Great King Dhṛtarāṣṭra. They are most renowned as celestial musicians who serve the gods. In the Abhidharma, the term is also used to refer to the mental body assumed by sentient beings during the intermediate state between death and rebirth. Gandharvas are said to live on fragrances (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003egandha\u003c/em\u003e) in the desire realm, hence the Tibetan translation \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edri za\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “scent eater.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"gandharva\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandharva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b4d79f26-3f86-4e27-9bc5-a20b80a606a4\",\"authority\":\"062f7b7f-39dc-4bcc-a998-f5cf2636a853\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe Gaṅgā, or Ganges in English, is considered to be the most sacred river of India, particularly within the Hindu tradition. It starts in the Himalayas, flows through the northern plains of India, bathing the holy city of Vārāṇasī, and meets the sea at the Bay of Bengal, in Bangladesh. In the sūtras, however, this river is mostly mentioned not for its sacredness but for its abundant sands‍—noticeable still today on its many sandy banks and at its delta‍—which serve as a common metaphor for infinitely large numbers.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eAccording to Buddhist cosmology, as explained in the \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eAbhidharmakośa\u003c/cite\u003e, it is one of the four rivers that flow from Lake Anavatapta and cross the southern continent of Jambudvīpa‍—the known human world or more specifically the Indian subcontinent. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gaṅgā\",\"tibetan\":\"གང་གཱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gaṅgā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gang gA\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7f1d9443-e4d8-4521-b596-af0fdd883164\",\"authority\":\"ba7579fc-ce40-4ade-b704-5f7d033091cc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eIn Indian mythology, the garuḍa is an eagle-like bird that is regarded as the king of all birds, normally depicted with a sharp, owl-like beak, often holding a snake, and with large and powerful wings. They are traditionally enemies of the nāgas. In the Vedas, they are said to have brought nectar from the heavens to earth. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eGaruḍa\u003c/em\u003e can also be used as a proper name for a king of such creatures.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"garuḍa\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་མཁའ་ལྡིང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"garuḍa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam mkha’ lding\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c974a79c-3c91-40fa-8a22-695c74a98754\",\"authority\":\"3e79f1d7-ef59-440d-ba18-0ece10d9d15b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"giving birth\",\"tibetan\":\"བུ་བཙའ་བའི་དུས་ན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prasavanakāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bu btsa’ ba’i dus na\"}},{\"uuid\":\"743aac3d-15fc-4192-be69-b05c5584d4ea\",\"authority\":\"87f6ed5d-68a9-4ddd-8744-81855f2d8943\",\"definition\":\"$2a\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"god\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"deva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a1044c3f-9cda-456d-9df9-65f615aa22f7\",\"authority\":\"457e3489-7179-488c-b0b0-6599dc3c6f85\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe deity who is born alongside and accompanies a being and is responsible for recording good and bad deeds to present before the Lord of Death \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-262\\\"\u003eYama\u003c/span\u003e when that being dies.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"god who was born with that person\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་དེ་དང་ལྷན་ཅིག་སྐྱེས་པའི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"puruṣasya sahajā pṛṣṭhānubaddhā devatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi de dang lhan cig skyes pa’i lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3ba5ea94-9e41-499a-bdfd-74e6f2650b7f\",\"authority\":\"28cb2ef8-10d7-49af-828d-9f7ca0e6d499\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"grain\",\"tibetan\":\"འབྲུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sasya, śasya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’bru\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2c78f096-4bf1-473f-8fc4-372315f0f7a1\",\"authority\":\"da0fa030-7db5-48be-b31f-6dde875428d5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe term for aspirations such as helping all beings, generating a buddhafield, bringing all beings to perfect awakening, and so forth that a bodhisattva makes while practicing bodhisattva conduct.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"great aspiration\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨོན་ལམ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahāpraṇidhāna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"smon lam chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"774fb7f2-7ff9-4d51-aa10-ed8bc69573a4\",\"authority\":\"00fd8425-966e-41af-87e7-4d4d22bb3814\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"great household, household\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིང་སཱ་ལ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahāśāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shing sA la chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d09252d2-d990-4e23-8cfe-5e673de4aa9f\",\"authority\":\"e620b442-25fb-476a-9a1c-ad274ca2c237\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"great yakṣa general\",\"tibetan\":\"གནོས་སྦྱིན་གྱི་སྡེ་དཔོན་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­yakṣa­senāpati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnos sbyin gyi sde dpon chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f48ae7a4-b1f3-49dc-9ccd-6019bb70351b\",\"authority\":\"5854fcf1-4f80-4dbc-b680-11070b8343da\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"have only one eye\",\"tibetan\":\"ཞར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kāṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zhar ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8b8f498c-e758-4bad-8642-f9055d61409e\",\"authority\":\"93f42f23-5f71-4743-bc05-bcc3e788905b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"hunchbacked\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒུར་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kubja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgur po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1fb3df06-5971-4968-a4b4-1ba24293e727\",\"authority\":\"43efcd46-3799-448c-afbe-2cf562ec6a14\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"hungry ghost realm\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡི་དགས་ཀྱི་འཇིག་རྟེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pretaloka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yi dags kyi ’jig rten\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8c676742-3af6-4860-98dd-7cfb3f89f721\",\"authority\":\"e3e99ae9-f98f-465c-a2cc-6d4bde7c89de\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"hyena\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tarakṣu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dred\"}},{\"uuid\":\"564d8ea9-dfb7-42ae-b9b9-c4b03389d607\",\"authority\":\"568df401-c6cf-4029-911b-4eee7bc58c79\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"illness, illnesses\",\"tibetan\":\"བྲོ་ནད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vyādhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bro nad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"62f33895-4037-4996-9cc5-124db625d5c8\",\"authority\":\"77669087-cee0-4720-b08d-f4c0276120e5\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"illuminate\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷམ་མེ་གྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhrājeran\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lham me gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6b20c315-faf7-4e18-a9df-6e2db860e228\",\"authority\":\"ac365037-bbdf-4dfe-bbdd-9cd75e376c3b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"impaired faculties\",\"tibetan\":\"དབང་པོ་མ་ཚང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vikalendriya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dbang po ma tshang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e2075711-98f5-47bf-a7d6-24b24b5a1755\",\"authority\":\"d23d072d-c7e3-411e-a8bd-837bcd758ea7\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"incorrect discipline\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚུལ་ཁྲིམས་ལོག་པར་ཞུགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śīlavipanna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshul khrims log par zhugs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"86cc91e1-b07e-470a-8443-ec8e77613db2\",\"authority\":\"39a56372-de69-4a69-8748-bdce0e2483c7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Indala\",\"tibetan\":\"དབང་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"indala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dbang ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"42c66fa6-6c95-4dd8-916d-b35febda3db4\",\"authority\":\"a87beec8-9bbb-49ec-9d68-5a89b9875823\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eJinamitra was invited to Tibet during the reign of King Tri Songdetsen (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ekhri srong lde btsan\u003c/em\u003e, r. 742–98 \u003cspan class=\\\"small-caps\\\"\u003eᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e) and was involved with the translation of nearly two hundred texts, continuing into the reign of King Ralpachen (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eral pa can\u003c/em\u003e, r. 815–38 \u003cspan class=\\\"small-caps\\\"\u003eᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e). He was one of the small group of paṇḍitas responsible for the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eMahāvyutpatti\u003c/cite\u003e Sanskrit–Tibetan dictionary.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Jinamitra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཛི་ན་མི་ཏྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jinamitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dzi na mi tra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"852d055a-c616-46a5-919b-e510b44302ee\",\"authority\":\"f89b323b-6879-4903-8c15-d766f03ccc83\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of spirit beings typically associated with violent sorcery rites.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"kākhorda\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kākhorda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"57349933-7c73-4afc-be37-dc4942be0146\",\"authority\":\"527c424b-8a4c-4030-b8ef-989098b2357b\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe emotional and cognitive veils that create impediments in one’s life and prevent one from seeing the nature of reality.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"karmic obscuration\",\"tibetan\":\"ལས་ཀྱི་སྒྲིབ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"karmāvaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"las kyi sgrib pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4fd75d88-000b-411e-95b1-ef38e2b6dacf\",\"authority\":\"9c1a3b12-642b-412a-ae0b-fe90b5ecde84\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Kiṃbhīra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཅི་འཇིགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kiṃbhīra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ci ’jigs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"454cf445-d5ac-4097-abe0-57f0069431f2\",\"authority\":\"b57a5182-b1eb-4168-bd5f-28ca6def5a9f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of shapeshifting beings. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"kinnara\",\"tibetan\":\"མིའམ་ཅི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kinnara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi’am ci\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d64414dc-ad29-4e9d-99b1-d700901d25ab\",\"authority\":\"7f981f55-b847-4d5d-931a-d6f5b6f58df6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe ruling caste in the traditional four-caste hierarchy of India, associated with warriors, the aristocracy, and kings.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"kṣatriya\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་རིགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kṣatriya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal rigs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"27fdcc40-002b-47b9-99ce-4f06b47bd269\",\"authority\":\"e83dcf25-1fc6-4584-8cae-ff65a7d107b6\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"lame\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡན་ལག་སྐྱོན་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"laṅga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yan lag skyon can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0e34a071-0c6d-4dab-abb9-d75191f75e4d\",\"authority\":\"bedf8b21-1bb8-470d-a355-c9d6faf1158e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"lunar eclipse\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟའ་ཟླ་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"candragraha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gza’ zla ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"110d8c9f-c4f8-4791-8f72-5f2534c607d9\",\"authority\":\"dc79c87e-1623-4495-bc0c-fcd606ba6620\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahāla\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨྲ་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"smra ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cfdda550-0a13-4865-9d54-4a8ac3e430bd\",\"authority\":\"eb1c6fc0-d2f8-4d3e-8fad-825f71769dd7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eLiterally “great serpents,” mahoragas are supernatural beings depicted as large, subterranean beings with human torsos and heads and the lower bodies of serpents. Their movements are said to cause earthquakes, and they make up a class of subterranean geomantic spirits whose movement through the seasons and months of the year is deemed significant for construction projects.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mahoraga\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྟོ་འཕྱེ་ཆེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahoraga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lto ’phye chen\"}},{\"uuid\":\"abe20072-53d9-4db9-a153-41172c50a57e\",\"authority\":\"5ca8d891-5282-4b94-a92c-7e8dff7daf1e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"make them shine, to make shine\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷང་ངེར་གྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"viroceran\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhang nger gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bd416713-18e1-4bcd-aa37-1255f4489642\",\"authority\":\"6781d355-d243-4239-a2e2-9a134b637fd7\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"manifest, manifested\",\"tibetan\":\"ལེགས་པར་གནས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratyupasthita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"legs par gnas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"445d93f2-7d72-4338-8d0d-41391ddd697a\",\"authority\":\"320c5523-4cde-4365-aeb1-3e69be9b0e42\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eSee “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-248\\\"\u003eMañjuśrī\u003c/span\u003e.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mañjuśrī, Mañjuśrīkumārabhūta\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇམ་དཔལ་གཞོན་ནུར་གྱུར་པ།, འཇམ་དཔལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mañjuśrī, mañjuśrī­kumāra­bhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jam dpal, ’jam dpal gzhon nur gyur pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a9d821a9-3cc6-4f11-94b6-c36ad0b6a6cb\",\"authority\":\"320c5523-4cde-4365-aeb1-3e69be9b0e42\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMañjuśrī is one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha” and a bodhisattva who embodies wisdom. He is a major figure in the Mahāyāna sūtras, appearing often as an interlocutor of the Buddha. In his most well-known iconographic form, he is portrayed bearing the sword of wisdom in his right hand and a volume of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ePrajñā­pāramitā­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e in his left. To his name, Mañjuśrī, meaning “Gentle and Glorious One,” is often added the epithet Kumārabhūta, “having a youthful form.” He is also called Mañjughoṣa, Mañjusvara, and Pañcaśikha.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAlso known here as \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-249\\\"\u003eMañjuśrīkumārabhūta\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mañjuśrī, Mañjuśrīkumārabhūta\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇམ་དཔལ་གཞོན་ནུར་གྱུར་པ།, འཇམ་དཔལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mañjuśrī, mañjuśrī­kumāra­bhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jam dpal, ’jam dpal gzhon nur gyur pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"30fce34c-e31e-4279-8a5c-69f1c3ca2f2f\",\"authority\":\"1f2c5cff-2505-474f-a76d-38701fb52951\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe being who orchestrates and perpetuates the illusion of cyclic existence. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Māra\",\"tibetan\":\"བདུད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"māra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bdud\"}},{\"uuid\":\"9d24c363-a19b-400e-af97-1e8b193f95d4\",\"authority\":\"5e533fd0-a2d3-435f-8e27-192dd80afff9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mekhila\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱན་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mekhila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyan ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"af444519-c053-4ef2-8495-5747d94de944\",\"authority\":\"b9a7292c-5af6-4b45-8a0a-c6ff2a57ddef\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mentally ill\",\"tibetan\":\"སྨྱོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"unmatta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"smyon pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a3efffd6-869a-4db9-82c5-eb27587847c2\",\"authority\":\"c2324eb1-dbfc-4051-a6f4-69ab84e3eb02\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"moon\",\"tibetan\":\"གདུང་ཟླ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"candra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gdung zla\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fa5cf5ef-0351-47e4-805f-80836b5b9e51\",\"authority\":\"c8fd71e6-f126-450d-a543-0e4be4e6fd46\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of spirit being.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mountain deity\",\"tibetan\":\"རིའི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"giridevatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ri’i lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a5150d0b-1631-40bb-9954-e296550132fa\",\"authority\":\"a8d2f676-e856-4bea-aabd-cd54000f070c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA tree in \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-270\\\"\u003eVaiśālī\u003c/span\u003e at whose base the Buddha Śākyamuni taught \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Blessed Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"musical tree\",\"tibetan\":\"རོལ་མོའི་སྒྲ་ཅན་གྱི་ཤིང་ལྗོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vādya­svara­vṛkṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rol mo’i sgra can gyi shing ljon pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"686d6042-1ae0-48bc-8b45-c65e4d770560\",\"authority\":\"03200e06-f99e-48f3-86ae-5590e5616e7a\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"necessities, provisions\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡོ་བྱད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upakaraṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yo byad\"}},{\"uuid\":\"92d18cd0-9466-4cbb-b56a-f9024cf037aa\",\"authority\":\"8f43f4c1-3a98-48b7-9d88-be86228608d0\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"nurse\",\"tibetan\":\"རིམ་གྲོ་བྱེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upastāpaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rim gro byed pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b6a88625-3190-47ab-ac85-1e7efddabef3\",\"authority\":\"06d351a1-7a97-426f-ae4b-4be4302139c3\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"one hundred inauspicious things\",\"tibetan\":\"བཀྲ་མི་ཤིས་པ་བརྒྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amaṅgalaśata, śatam alakṣmīṇām\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bkra mi shis pa brgya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"facdabe4-db2f-4a2a-b57f-3af989136f31\",\"authority\":\"b89de939-fff8-4c8f-bbad-940b76851f88\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"overcome by greed\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆགས་པས་ཟིལ་གྱིས་ནོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"lobhābhibhūta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chags pas zil gyis non pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5030ca25-2021-4c21-99f8-1b68d07379f0\",\"authority\":\"db2ec71e-a5d6-47c0-a15e-1dd94b3d681b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"overcome by pride, overcome by their pride\",\"tibetan\":\"ང་རྒྱལ་གྱིས་ནོན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mānastabdha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nga rgyal gyis non pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"358e5588-9c32-470d-94b9-7e777ada653d\",\"authority\":\"bf2568e2-fbcb-44d0-9f11-6578a0a0ac17\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Pāyila\",\"tibetan\":\"བཏུང་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pāyila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"btung ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d6f93d29-178b-4a14-ba1a-eb22ecdbb656\",\"authority\":\"839bd74c-b512-4eb5-bf20-b21ca8dcaac8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"persecuted by many acts of treachery\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྱུ་དུ་མས་ཀུན་དུ་བཙེས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anekamāyābhir upadrutaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgyu du mas kun du btses pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8d4ef3a7-2978-4621-82de-11366f4c2bda\",\"authority\":\"5830463c-615e-4a92-a4cd-68f3a648081d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of nonhuman beings that, like several other classes of nonhuman beings, take spontaneous birth. Ranking below rākṣasas, they are less powerful and more akin to pretas. They are said to dwell in impure and perilous places, where they feed on impure things, including flesh. This could account for the name \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epiśāca\u003c/em\u003e, which possibly derives from \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003e√piś\u003c/em\u003e, to carve or chop meat, as reflected also in the Tibetan \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esha za\u003c/em\u003e, “meat eater.” They are often described as having an unpleasant appearance, and at times they appear with animal bodies. Some possess the ability to enter the dead bodies of humans, thereby becoming so-called \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003evetāla\u003c/em\u003e, to touch whom is fatal.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"piśāca\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤ་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"piśāca\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sha za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6cd0f088-644b-42e1-b97d-fb9926358f45\",\"authority\":\"cc3fd873-35b9-4db6-ad90-ee34a8ed5a50\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"poor complexion\",\"tibetan\":\"མདོག་ངན་པ།, མདོག་མི་སྡུག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"durvarṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mdog mi sdug pa, mdog ngan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"89913917-2506-4297-9321-91c13315a95d\",\"authority\":\"5bd7e95c-02f3-4226-96a8-42daad907e2c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBrahman\u003c/em\u003e is a Sanskrit term referring to what is highest (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eparama\u003c/em\u003e) and most important (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epradhāna\u003c/em\u003e); the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eNibandhana\u003c/cite\u003e commentary explains \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ebrahman\u003c/em\u003e as meaning here \u003cem class=\\\"distinct\\\"\u003enirvāṇa\u003c/em\u003e, and thus the brahman conduct is the “conduct toward brahman,” the conduct that leads to the highest liberation, i.e., nirvāṇa. This is explained as “the path without outflows,” which is the “truth of the path” among the four truths of the noble ones. Other explanations (found in the Pāli tradition) take “brahman conduct” to mean the “best conduct,” and also the “conduct of the best,” i.e., the buddhas. In some contexts, “brahman conduct” refers more specifically to celibacy, but the specific referents of this expression are many.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"practice pure conduct\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པར་སྤྱད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmacarya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs par spyad pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e1894c5d-a0ba-4881-b9aa-06595e73a72a\",\"authority\":\"c0fc2af2-094e-4418-b5b6-4076fdf24c4a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThese basic precepts are five in number for the laity: (1) not killing, (2) not stealing, (3) chastity, (4) not lying, and (5) avoiding intoxicants. For monks, there are three or five more; avoidance of such things as perfumes, makeup, ointments, garlands, high beds, and afternoon meals. (\u003cem class=\\\"distinct\\\"\u003eProvisional 84000 definition. New definition forthcoming.\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"precept\",\"tibetan\":\"བསླབ་པའི་གནས།, བསླབ་པའི་གཞི།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śikṣāpada\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bslab pa’i gnas, bslab pa’i gzhi\"}},{\"uuid\":\"61341a33-bb84-4c65-8382-d6f5bebc078b\",\"authority\":\"a7d72d54-e170-4d4b-ad8a-e598ffa3c666\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"province\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲོང་རྡལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"janapada\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grong rdal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cf691324-2de5-4910-a68b-c593bd039986\",\"authority\":\"7f2df430-f1d1-4706-8d1e-67e79f37c2ae\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA term describing the quality of a being’s intellect. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"prudent\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡིད་བཞུངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"medhāvin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yid bzhungs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a92c6bc2-f95b-4cbf-a5a1-f9852990aa52\",\"authority\":\"e695b684-0ed5-429c-a871-1b5543e2f34f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn alternate title for \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Purifying All Karmic Obscurations and Fulfilling All Hopes\",\"tibetan\":\"ལས་ཀྱི་སྒྲུབ་པ་ཐམས་ཅད་རྣམ་པར་སྦྱོང་ཞིང་རེ་བ་ཐམས་ཅད་ཡོངས་སུ་སྐོང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"las kyi sgrub pa thams cad rnam par sbyong zhing re ba thams cad yongs su skong ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a8eda40a-7fdf-45b4-9578-016ac782cdfb\",\"authority\":\"876d2af6-1945-40b0-a434-a0a06775fa7e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of nonhuman beings that are often, but certainly not always, considered demonic in the Buddhist tradition. They are often depicted as flesh-eating monsters who haunt frightening places and are ugly and evil-natured with a yearning for human flesh, and who additionally have miraculous powers, such as being able to change their appearance.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"rākṣasa\",\"tibetan\":\"སྲིན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rākṣasa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"srin po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"010afd3a-1318-4adf-b782-5f146d3b3864\",\"authority\":\"9fb0ca63-5857-4d48-ad24-772eb0616c6e\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"riches\",\"tibetan\":\"དབྱིག\",\"sanskrit\":\"vasu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dbyig\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1c539450-6a9f-4fab-ad3d-03ec7d50e2f7\",\"authority\":\"2e5a3823-eba6-4771-8209-c394a2b977df\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eTibetan short form of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-237\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/span\u003e, also known as the Medicine Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sangyé Menla\",\"tibetan\":\"སངས་རྒྱས་སྨན་བླ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sangs rgyas sman bla\"}},{\"uuid\":\"06f133d6-c3b0-4015-b926-2127cecd545b\",\"authority\":\"7981c027-b1db-4f47-b6ac-a587f2b934d4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Saṇṭhila\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་བཅས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saṇṭhila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas bcas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3b187882-e6cb-4302-af05-5ee65dbe3225\",\"authority\":\"5d9ab7d8-f992-407e-beee-219ff9875106\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIndian commentator from the eighth century (685–783 \u003cspan class=\\\"small-caps\\\"\u003eᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e) renowned for his work \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Way of the Bodhisattva\u003c/cite\u003e (\u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBodhi­caryāvatāra\u003c/cite\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śāntideva\",\"tibetan\":\"ཞི་བ་ལྷ།, ཞི་བའི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāntideva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"zhi ba lha, zhi ba’i lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"db7650ff-bc0e-471e-be3c-1eecbf646266\",\"authority\":\"ebaa28bb-7186-4a9d-b019-54ba108a4555\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"scorpion\",\"tibetan\":\"སྡིག\",\"sanskrit\":\"vṛścika\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sdig\"}},{\"uuid\":\"07e61ab3-fa98-4b8c-9c5c-daeb0e0e41e3\",\"authority\":\"f3fd44bd-5c36-4413-be26-791047ebcfde\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sense pleasures\",\"tibetan\":\"འདོད་པའི་ཡོན་ཏན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kāmaguṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’dod pa’i yon tan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7fe482cf-d978-4cbb-ab88-49d8247867f7\",\"authority\":\"270510d2-5d9e-4a8c-8b26-b0bbb6747be0\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sentenced to death\",\"tibetan\":\"གསད་པར་འོས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vadhārha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gsad par ’os pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2940c04f-befa-42ef-b5bf-3e8d49cd973e\",\"authority\":\"52322944-8a7f-47f2-aff9-48472209b78e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe set of seven precious materials or substances includes a range of precious metals and gems, but their exact list varies. The set often consists of gold, silver, beryl, crystal, red pearls, emeralds, and white coral, but may also contain lapis lazuli, ruby, sapphire, chrysoberyl, diamonds, etc. The term is frequently used in the sūtras to exemplify preciousness, wealth, and beauty, and can describe treasures, offering materials, or the features of architectural structures such as stūpas, palaces, thrones, etc. The set is also used to describe the beauty and prosperity of buddha realms and the realms of the gods.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn other contexts, the term \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esaptaratna\u003c/em\u003e can also refer to the seven precious possessions of a cakravartin or to a set of seven precious moral qualities. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"seven precious substances\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བདུན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"saptaratna\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che sna bdun\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e027cc95-c6fb-48fa-ae75-2c7be803ad4b\",\"authority\":\"08dc6ac2-dc3d-4cef-8bc2-38da137b5985\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe special methods that enlightened beings use to lead other beings to awakening. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"skillful means\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐབས་མཁས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"upāyakauśalya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thabs mkhas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"37132f8a-2d9a-405d-8b6a-c899623077bd\",\"authority\":\"10e90b13-2654-4b96-ba5d-57c23053afc6\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"solar eclipse\",\"tibetan\":\"གཟའ་ཉི་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūryagraha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gza’ nyi ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1dc4c134-d9bb-4617-ad63-e08428e8d369\",\"authority\":\"fe61fd73-1613-4c34-b55d-55be22a044be\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe places between adjacent world systems, outside their defining ring of mountains, that are said to be miserable and in utter darkness as the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-208\\\"\u003esuns\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-182\\\"\u003emoons\u003c/span\u003e of the world systems can shed no light there. They are nevertheless said to be inhabited by numerous beings and are sometimes counted among the hell realms.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Spaces between worlds\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་བར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"lokāntarikā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jig rten gyi bar\"}},{\"uuid\":\"09958f58-ba6d-4995-a901-ce2cb255aa36\",\"authority\":\"ee947dd0-b641-41d5-8fae-fb48bfdc2b12\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eŚrīmitra (d. 343), a prince from Kucha (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-zh\\\" lang=\\\"zh\\\"\u003e龜茲\u003c/em\u003e, Qiuci, in the Tarim Basin on the Silk Road, present-day Kuqa in Xinjiang), who lived one generation before the other famous Kuchean translator, Kumārajīva. Kucha at the time was a culturally Indic, Tocharian-speaking kingdom. Śrīmitra abdicated the throne in favor of his younger brother and became a monk and translator, traveling to China. He spent 307–312 in Luoyang (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-zh\\\" lang=\\\"zh\\\"\u003e洛陽\u003c/em\u003e) where he translated Taishō 1331 mentioned here, later moving to Jiankang (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-zh\\\" lang=\\\"zh\\\"\u003e建康\u003c/em\u003e). He was responsible for introducing a number of other Buddhist texts and dhāraṇīs to China. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śrīmitra\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrīmitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"beb14c8c-22c9-4cbb-b14c-392f2edf214b\",\"authority\":\"ee7d2018-ef1c-4e07-ba2b-96766a051058\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"statue\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐུ་གཟུགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pratimā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sku gzugs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8552f074-9293-4a88-b611-021b0144e664\",\"authority\":\"d95b877a-2b72-41be-b3cc-f2d685b92fc8\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"strength of a great champion\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚན་པོ་ཆེ་ཆེན་པོའི་སྟོབས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­nagnabala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshan po che chen po’i stobs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"041e2923-fe02-4270-a362-a95100f2fb76\",\"authority\":\"d90b157d-b522-4df3-8bb3-0e2b4938a3fd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe buddhafield of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003eThus-Gone\u003c/span\u003e Amitābha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེ་བ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sukhāvatī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bde ba can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4748cce8-fecc-4fe4-a21d-dc3701240e0a\",\"authority\":\"00c9880b-c835-42e4-8a54-7f9d0c52c4a4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eAccording to ancient Buddhist cosmology, this is the great mountain forming the axis of the universe. At its summit is Sudarśana, home of Śakra and his thirty-two gods, and on its flanks live the asuras. The mount has four sides facing the cardinal directions, each of which is made of a different precious stone. Surrounding it are several mountain ranges and the great ocean where the four principal island continents lie: in the south, Jambudvīpa (our world); in the west, Godānīya; in the north, Uttarakuru; and in the east, Pūrvavideha. Above it are the abodes of the desire realm gods. It is variously referred to as Meru, Mount Meru, Sumeru, and Mount Sumeru.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sumeru\",\"tibetan\":\"རི་རབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sumeru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ri rab\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2a81074e-debf-4316-bb23-3177c8323be0\",\"authority\":\"20b1cda3-ae6f-46e1-b3cb-ba94d77fb17d\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"sun\",\"tibetan\":\"གདུགས།, ཉི་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūrya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gdugs, nyi ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"529e1b37-d121-4652-87c7-d7915abc2d68\",\"authority\":\"7a0811db-90af-4718-83b0-cc6e35dc9e28\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the two primary bodhisattvas who accompany the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003eThus-Gone One\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-238\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\u003c/span\u003e in the buddhafield \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-269\\\"\u003eVaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sūrya­vairocana\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉི་མ་ལྟར་རྣམ་པར་སྣང་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sūrya­vairocana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyi ma ltar rnam par snang byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"de5e647c-c6c1-4234-a117-24bf05b39370\",\"authority\":\"b6752fcb-94b2-4bc5-9586-0d96ab171078\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eIn addition to the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-154\\\"\u003efive precepts\u003c/span\u003e of abstaining from (1) killing, (2) stealing, (3) sexual misconduct, (4) lying, and (5) intoxication, the \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003eten precepts\u003c/span\u003e often include (the list varies) abstaining from (6) eating after the midday meal, (7) dancing, singing, or engaging in other forms of entertainments, (8) wearing jewelry or adorning oneself with cosmetics, (9) using high or luxurious beds or seats, and (10) handling money.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ten precepts\",\"tibetan\":\"བསླབ་པའི་གཞི་བཅུ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"daśaśikṣāpada\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bslab pa’i gzhi bcu po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eb8e546c-1abf-4180-a5a9-35e9e80bbc92\",\"authority\":\"5829cbde-4acd-426a-abfe-837963bdda67\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAbstaining from killing, taking what is not given, sexual misconduct, lying, uttering divisive talk, speaking harsh words, gossiping, covetousness, ill will, and wrong views.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"ten virtuous actions\",\"tibetan\":\"དགེ་བ་བཅུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"daśakuśala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dge ba bcu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"39a596fd-ae1e-4ea2-a33a-142455b04d46\",\"authority\":\"29f97edc-9545-4770-8d45-89dfc46c2fb2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn alternate title for \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"The Bodhisattva Vajrapāṇi’s Vow\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ལག་ན་རྡོ་རྗེས་དམ་བཅས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub sems dpa’ lag na rdo rjes dam bcas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"525e4fe0-4211-4001-be3b-71be5fc642d5\",\"authority\":\"a8904b4b-8862-45d7-9749-e7a087aeb6fd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn alternate title for \u003ccite class=\\\"title text-en\\\" lang=\\\"en\\\"\u003eThe Detailed Account of the Previous Aspirations of the Thus-Gone Bhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"The Vows of the Twelve Great Yakṣa Generals\",\"tibetan\":\"གནོད་སྦྱིན་གྱི་སྡེ་དཔོན་ཆེན་པོ་བཅུ་གཉིས་ཀྱིས་དམ་བཅས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnod sbyin gyi sde dpon chen po bcu gnyis kyis dam bcas pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"392ef282-a172-45b8-a156-169992eaa417\",\"authority\":\"7eb71c16-59ac-4550-ae75-37713adc626e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThirty-two of the 112 identifying physical characteristics of both buddhas and \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-221\\\"\u003euniversal emperors\u003c/span\u003e, in addition to the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-153\\\"\u003eeighty minor marks\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"thirty-two marks of a great person\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱེས་བུ་ཆེན་པོའི་མཚན་སུམ་ཅུ་རྩ་གཉིས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dvātriṃśanmahā­puruṣa­lakṣaṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skyes bu chen po’i mtshan sum cu rtsa gnyis\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fc87d09b-c219-4d0b-b7d9-e0a5b9b08fa3\",\"authority\":\"3435d203-edf9-471c-a63a-6df4ffefe67e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThere are two common sets of “the \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003ethree vows\u003c/span\u003e.” The first set refers to the pratimokṣa, bodhicitta, and mantra vows, and this schema was perhaps most famously promoted in Tibet by the thirteenth-century Tibetan polymath Sakya Paṇḍita. The second set, which is likely the set of \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003ethree vows\u003c/span\u003e referred to here, consists of (1) the pratimokṣa vows (Tib. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003eso thar gyi sdom pa\u003c/em\u003e) of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-148\\\"\u003edesire\u003c/span\u003e realm, (2) the \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edhyāna\u003c/em\u003e vows (Tib. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esam gtan gyi sdom pa\u003c/em\u003e) of the form realm, and (3) the uncontaminated vows (Tib. \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ezag med kyi sdom pa\u003c/em\u003e) maintained by those who have transcended the three realms and are at the level of a noble being. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"three vows\",\"tibetan\":\"སྡོམ་པ་གསུམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"trisaṃvara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sdom pa gsum\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d5b4d6b9-6850-42c5-81c8-ea781b61a47b\",\"authority\":\"285a8525-75c9-4ab3-8d61-e257c5eb21ce\",\"definition\":\"$2b\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"thus-gone, thus-gone one\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་བཞིན་གཤེགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tathāgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de bzhin gshegs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7ffcb8b3-8a44-4a6d-b2b0-2a6a468bb773\",\"authority\":\"05efb8d1-36d5-45a6-abbe-c17706155a41\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"to warm, warm them\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷན་ནེར་གྱུར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tapyeran\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhan ner gyur\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5bd3e979-9d9a-4c4d-bb03-6ccdf1e97b0f\",\"authority\":\"e65426f5-1981-45f0-a362-81e4e30ebe9c\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"tortured\",\"tibetan\":\"གོ་རར་གཞུག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"avaruddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"go rar gzhug pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d815746b-a5c7-43a9-9413-36e91607242f\",\"authority\":\"92c3161c-282d-4882-85ab-7d026e8d635b\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"town\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲོང་ཁྱེར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nagara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grong khyer\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e395621c-5852-46eb-a457-65b28596d6db\",\"authority\":\"ab164684-3289-4455-b79a-98d9a8ca097d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA bodhisattva. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Trāṇamukta\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐྱབས་གྲོལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"trāṇamukta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skyabs grol\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a7b884d2-a341-46dc-9ca7-bd5a6a73eaa3\",\"authority\":\"e45a450e-5ac2-4518-9f4f-ef46651c8f57\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of spirit being.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"tree deity\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིང་གི་ལྷ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vṛkṣadevatā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shing gi lha\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7d39cc5d-256c-4e30-9eb9-c28731cd772c\",\"authority\":\"7ddeac12-08fe-4b7a-9066-f1a0d49dbc64\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"turret\",\"tibetan\":\"བ་གམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"niryūha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ba gam\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7f20ccc0-0a8d-4dec-950e-cd7f6b8a868b\",\"authority\":\"37f1d3ce-ffe3-45dc-9930-a8106b865939\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"uncorrupted discipline\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚུལ་ཁྲིམས་ཉམས་པ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akhaṇḍaśīla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshul khrims nyams pa med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"faed50ce-2e2a-4b67-8628-9d65feeacf17\",\"authority\":\"a4267ba1-f3d9-47a7-90c9-a1f25b234cfe\",\"definition\":\"$2c\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"universal emperor\",\"tibetan\":\"འཁོར་ལོས་སྒྱུར་བའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cakravartin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’khor los sgyur ba’i rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4606878a-3e90-40c6-97cb-1c3fd3ed91b8\",\"authority\":\"49f3b97e-688d-42ac-96d6-d6d5e810a7ff\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe buddhafield of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-213\\\"\u003eThus-Gone\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-238\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\",\"tibetan\":\"བཻ་ཌཱུརྱ་ར་སྣང་བ།, བཻ་ཌཱུརྱ་སྣང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiḍūrya­nirbhāsa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bai DUr+ya ra snang ba, bai DUr+ya snang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"87030664-4985-441c-8cbd-801b543ca41e\",\"authority\":\"1935a229-0372-406e-8848-47fd7cb522de\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of a number of \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003etowns\u003c/span\u003e where the Buddha Śākyamuni is said to have taught.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vaiśālī\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡངས་པ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiśālī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yangs pa can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a1fa155f-36e0-401d-a60d-712b3fabb65a\",\"authority\":\"9060d43c-24ad-46f9-bc21-032ef7c9c350\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vajra\",\"tibetan\":\"རྡོ་རྗེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vajra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdo rje\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d9a23ad2-63f7-4616-88b3-31158ce56f97\",\"authority\":\"3d58ef2a-3ca7-41be-bc51-6e392c9774e7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eVajrapāṇi means “Wielder of the Vajra.” In the Pali canon, he appears as a yakṣa guardian in the retinue of the Buddha. In the Mahāyāna scriptures he is a bodhisattva and one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha.” In the tantras, he is also regarded as an important Buddhist deity and instrumental in the transmission of tantric scriptures. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vajrapāṇi\",\"tibetan\":\"ལག་ན་རྡོ་རྗེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vajrapāṇi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lag na rdo rje\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c055f6d1-0659-4747-9503-bc39840c812f\",\"authority\":\"e03d7648-4ce5-49e6-b28c-8a7e466b248e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA class of spirit beings typically associated with violent sorcery rites, the \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003evetāla\u003c/span\u003e is most often described as a reanimated corpse or zombie. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"vetāla\",\"tibetan\":\"རོ་ལངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vetāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ro langs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b7c0a199-3d98-48e5-b26b-d7bd4160c4f2\",\"authority\":\"d6630e2f-81b3-4bd4-84c0-74532680cfa9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eOne of the twelve \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-087-009-164\\\"\u003egreat yakṣa generals\u003c/span\u003e who protect and serve those who bear, read, recite, copy, or commission a copy of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eBhaiṣajya­guru­vaiḍūrya­prabha­rāja­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vikala\",\"tibetan\":\"རྫོགས་བྱེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vikala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdzogs byed\"}},{\"uuid\":\"44261343-92a8-413c-b583-04ba1878db62\",\"authority\":\"c3a5ba39-2af1-4aa5-b3f5-dfc9e9a471cf\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"village\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲོང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"grāma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grong\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eacc31bd-07db-41db-92db-0e8df3e6355d\",\"authority\":\"71a5df3f-445d-4a87-830a-28704d2c36dd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe principle of vital warmth and action throughout the body.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"vital energy\",\"tibetan\":\"མདངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ojas\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mdangs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"60745c47-72d0-4e49-a4af-57aecdb4b9e6\",\"authority\":\"52362a1f-c7dc-4e32-91c6-57b639146424\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"vitiligo\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤ་བཀྲ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śvitra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sha bkra\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1fb8ada2-2a72-4c2d-9dda-1c75c27fc89f\",\"authority\":\"1eff3ddd-94f6-4cbe-ad8b-01a916af4f50\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"weak constitution\",\"tibetan\":\"ལུས་ངན་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"hīnakāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lus ngan pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7592fd85-fafc-42db-a077-641db438c9e7\",\"authority\":\"fc965dd1-9cdf-4f53-8237-8f46fa92b287\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"wealth\",\"tibetan\":\"ལོངས་སྤྱོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhoga\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"longs spyod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b342c5a1-c902-458a-8eff-a8142a795d0b\",\"authority\":\"86fdb910-00c6-42c6-8c8f-4e57fe1c4b9e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe world of the Lord of Death.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"world of Yama\",\"tibetan\":\"གཤིན་རྗེའི་འཇིག་རྟེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yamaloka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gshin rje’i ’jig rten\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5d1d861a-9a7d-45ee-9d4e-a843c5698e55\",\"authority\":\"6bc88464-d01f-41dd-83e3-906807fba845\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of nonhuman beings who inhabit forests, mountainous areas, and other natural spaces, or serve as guardians of villages and towns, and may be propitiated for health, wealth, protection, and other boons, or controlled through magic. According to tradition, their homeland is in the north, where they live under the rule of the Great King Vaiśravaṇa.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e Several members of this class have been deified as gods of wealth (these include the just-mentioned Vaiśravaṇa) or as bodhisattva generals of yakṣa armies, and have entered the Buddhist pantheon in a variety of forms, including, in tantric Buddhism, those of wrathful deities.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"yakṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"གནོད་སྦྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yakṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnod sbyin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"33413e9d-f28e-40a7-8f31-b28134daf81b\",\"authority\":\"da44adf0-9a05-47f8-aebf-0a5485d7dbea\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe Lord of Death. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yama\",\"tibetan\":\"གཤིན་རྗེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yama\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gshin rje\"}}]}]\n"])</script><div hidden id="S:5"><div dir="ltr" data-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs" class="flex flex-col w-full gap-0 @container/sidebar"><div class="sticky top-0 pt-1 pb-2 z-10 w-full rounded-t bg-background overflow-x-auto text-center"><div role="tablist" aria-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs-list" class="bg-background gap-1 sm:gap-3 h-10 items-center justify-center sm:p-1 w-fit px-6 inline-flex mx-auto rounded-none" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" style="outline:none"><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-endnotes" data-state="active" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-endnotes" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring